When the WebLogic plugin is enabled, a call to getRemoteAddr will return the address of the browser client from the proprietary WL-Proxy-Client-IP header instead of the web server.

serverJDBCLoginTimeoutSeconds.name: serverJDBCLoginTimeoutSeconds
serverJDBCLoginTimeoutSeconds.description: Get the JDBC Login Timeout value. Specified value is passed into java.sql.DriverManager.setLoginTimeout(). Note that this DriverManager setting will impact *all* JDBC drivers loaded into this JVM. Feature is disabled by default.

serverClasspathServletDisabled.name: serverClasspathServletDisabled
serverClasspathServletDisabled.description: The ClasspathServlet will serve any class file in the classpath and is registered by default in every Web application (including management). It does not need to be turned on for many applications though, and represents a security hole if unchecked.

serverIdleConnectionTimeout.name: serverIdleConnectionTimeout
serverIdleConnectionTimeout.description: The maximum number of seconds that a connection is allowed to be idle before it is closed by the server. The T3 and T3S protocols ignore this attribute. If you configure network channels for this server, each channel can override this idle connection message timeout. This timeout helps guard against server deadlock through too many open connections.

serverDefaultInternalServletsDisabled.name: serverDefaultInternalServletsDisabled
serverDefaultInternalServletsDisabled.description: Specifies whether all default servlets in the servlet engine are disabled. This includes: weblogic.servlet.ClasspathServlet weblogic.servlet.utils.iiop.GetIORServlet weblogic.rjvm.http.TunnelSendServlet weblogic.rjvm.http.TunnelRecvServlet weblogic.rjvm.http.TunnelLoginServlet weblogic.rjvm.http.TunnelCloseServlet If set to true, this property overrides the ClasspathServletDisabled property.

serverMaxMessageSize.name: serverMaxMessageSize
serverMaxMessageSize.description: The maximum number of bytes allowed in messages that are received over all supported protocols, unless overridden by a protocol-specific setting or a custom channel setting. The order of precedence for setting message size maximums is as follows: A channel-wide maximum in a custom network channel. A protocol-specific setting in the default network channel. See {@link #MaxCOMMessageSize MaxCOMMessageSize} {@link #MaxHTTPMessageSize MaxHTTPMessageSize} {@link #MaxIIOPMessageSize MaxIIOPessageSize} {@link #MaxT3MessageSize MaxT3MessageSize} The message maximum in this attribute. This maximum message size helps guard against a denial of service attack in which a caller attempts to force the server to allocate more memory than is available thereby keeping the server from responding quickly to other requests.

serverCustomTrustKeyStoreType.name: serverCustomTrustKeyStoreType
serverCustomTrustKeyStoreType.description: The type of the keystore. Generally, this is JKS. If empty or null, then the JDK's default keystore type (specified in java.security) is used. This keystore type is only used if KeyStores is CUSTOM_IDENTITY_AND_CUSTOM_TRUST.

serverListenersBindEarly.name: serverListenersBindEarly
serverListenersBindEarly.description: Determines whether the server should bind server sockets early. Early binding detects port conflicts quickly and also gives user feedback on the default listen port as to the server state.

serverLowMemoryTimeInterval.name: serverLowMemoryTimeInterval
serverLowMemoryTimeInterval.description: The amount of time (in seconds) that defines the interval over which this server determines average free memory values. By default, the server obtains an average free memory value every 3600 seconds. This interval is not used if the JRockit VM is used, as the memory samples are collected immediately after a VM-scheduled garbage collection. Taking memory samples after a garbage collection gives a more accurate average value of the free memory.

serverTransactionLogFileWritePolicy.name: serverTransactionLogFileWritePolicy
serverTransactionLogFileWritePolicy.description: The policy that determines how transaction log file entries are written to disk. This policy can affect transaction performance. (Note: To be transactionally safe, the Direct-Write policy may require additional OS or environment changes on some Windows systems.) WebLogic Server supports the following policies: Cache-Flush. Flushes operating system and on-disk caches after each write. Direct-Write. Tells the operating system to write directly to disk with each write. Direct-Write performs better than Cache-Flush and is available on Windows, HP-UX, and Solaris. If Direct-Write is not supported on the host platform, the policy becomes Cache-Flush and a log message is printed. Note: On Windows, unlike Solaris and HP, the 'Direct-Write' policy may leave transaction data in the on-disk cache without writing it to disk immediately. This is not transactionally safe because a power failure can cause loss of on-disk cache data. For transactionally safe writes using 'Direct-Write' on Windows, either disable all write caching for the disk (enabled by default), or use a disk with a battery-backed cache. The on-disk cache for a hard-drive on Windows can be disabled through system administration: Control-Panel -> System -> Hardware-tab -> Device-Manager-button -> Disk-Drives -> name-of-drive -> Policies-tab -> 'Enable write caching on the disk' check-box. Some file systems do not allow this value to be changed. For example, a RAID system that has a reliable cache.

serverKeyStores.name: serverKeyStores
serverKeyStores.description: Which configuration rules should be used for finding the server's identity and trust keystores?

serverAutoMigrationEnabled.name: serverAutoMigrationEnabled
serverAutoMigrationEnabled.description: Specifies whether Node Manager can automatically restart this server and its services on another machine if the server fails.

serverPeriodLength.name: serverPeriodLength
serverPeriodLength.description: The time interval in milliseconds of the heartbeat period. A value of 0 indicates that heartbeats are turned off.

serverStuckThreadTimerInterval.name: serverStuckThreadTimerInterval
serverStuckThreadTimerInterval.description: The number of seconds after which WebLogic Server periodically scans threads to see if they have been continually working for the configured maximum length of time.

serverDGCIdlePeriodsUntilTimeout.name: serverDGCIdlePeriodsUntilTimeout
serverDGCIdlePeriodsUntilTimeout.description: The number of idle periods allowed before object is collected.

serverHealthCheckIntervalSeconds.name: serverHealthCheckIntervalSeconds
serverHealthCheckIntervalSeconds.description: The number of seconds that defines the frequency of this server's self-health monitoring. The server monitors the health of it's subsystems every HealthCheckIntervalSeconds and changes the Server's overall state if required.

serverRestartIntervalSeconds.name: serverRestartIntervalSeconds
serverRestartIntervalSeconds.description: The number of seconds during which this server can be restarted, up to the number of times specified in RestartMax.

serverIdlePeriodsUntilTimeout.name: serverIdlePeriodsUntilTimeout
serverIdlePeriodsUntilTimeout.description: The number of idle periods until peer is considered unreachable

serverCustomTrustKeyStoreFileName.name: serverCustomTrustKeyStoreFileName
serverCustomTrustKeyStoreFileName.description: The path and file name of the custom trust keystore. The path name must either be absolute or relative to where the server was booted. This file name is only used if KeyStores is CUSTOM_IDENTITY_AND_CUSTOM_TRUST.

serverHostsMigratableServices.name: serverHostsMigratableServices
serverHostsMigratableServices.description: Gets the hostsMigratableServices attribute of the ServerMBean object

serverExternalDNSName.name: serverExternalDNSName
serverExternalDNSName.description: The external IP address or DNS name for this server. This address will be sent with HTTP session cookies and with dynamic server lists to HTTP proxies. It will also be used by external application clients to enable the propagation of RMI traffic through network address translating (NAT) firewalls. You must specify an external DNS name for configurations in which a firewall is performing network address translation, unless clients are accessing WebLogic Server using t3 and the default channel. For example, define the external DNS name for configurations in which a firewall is performing network address translation, and clients are accessing WebLogic Server using HTTP via a proxy plug-in.

serverOutboundPrivateKeyEnabled.name: serverOutboundPrivateKeyEnabled
serverOutboundPrivateKeyEnabled.description: Specifies whether the SSL identity specified by {@link SSLMBean#ServerPrivateKeyAlias SSLMBean#ServerPrivateKeyAlias} for this server should be used for outbound SSL connections on the default server channel. In normal circumstances the outbound identity is determined by the caller's environment.

serverAdministrationProtocol.name: serverAdministrationProtocol
serverAdministrationProtocol.description: Returns the protocol to be used for administrative connections when none is specified.

serverCustomIdentityKeyStoreType.name: serverCustomIdentityKeyStoreType
serverCustomIdentityKeyStoreType.description: The type of the keystore. Generally, this is JKS. If empty or null, then the JDK's default keystore type (specified in java.security) is used. The custom identity key store type is only used if KeyStores is CUSTOM_IDENTITY_AND_JAVA_STANDARD_TRUST, CUSTOM_IDENTITY_AND_CUSTOM_TRUST or CUSTOM_IDENTITY_AND_COMMAND_LINE_TRUST.

serverStartupMode.name: serverStartupMode
serverStartupMode.description: The state in which this server should be started. If you specify STANDBY, you must also enable the domain-wide administration port. In the RUNNING state, a server offers its services to clients and can operate as a full member of a cluster. In the ADMIN state, the server is up and running, but available only for administration operations, allowing you to perform server and application-level administration tasks without risk to running applications. In the STANDBY state, a server instance does not process any request; its regular Listen Port is closed. The Administration Port is open. It only accepts life cycle commands that transition the server instance to either the RUNNING or the SHUTDOWN state. Other Administration requests are not accepted. A STANDBYserver's only purpose is to resume into the RUNNING state quickly; it saves server startup time.

serverNMSocketCreateTimeoutInMillis.name: serverNMSocketCreateTimeoutInMillis
serverNMSocketCreateTimeoutInMillis.description: Returns the timeout value to be used by NodeManagerRuntime when creating a a socket connection to the agent.

serverStartTable.name: serverStartTable
serverStartTable.description: This table represents a serverStart in the domain.

serverStartIndex.name: serverStartIndex
serverStartIndex.description: Unique value directed from ObjectName which is used as table index

serverStartParent.name: serverStartParent
serverStartParent.description: BEA-proprietary Parent object's identification, with syntax <type>:<name>

serverStartArguments.name: serverStartArguments
serverStartArguments.description: The startup arguments to use when starting this server.

serverStartBeaHome.name: serverStartBeaHome
serverStartBeaHome.description: Returns the BEA home to be used to start this server. Note that this * path is on the remote machine.

serverStartClassPath.name: serverStartClassPath
serverStartClassPath.description: Set the classpath to be used to start this server. Note that this path * is on the remote machine.

serverStartJavaHome.name: serverStartJavaHome
serverStartJavaHome.description: The Java home directory (on the remote machine) to use when starting * this server. The java binary (or java.exe executable in Windows) is * taken from the Java home /bin directory to start the managed server.

serverStartRootDirectory.name: serverStartRootDirectory
serverStartRootDirectory.description: Returns the RootDirectory to be used to start this server. Note that this * path is on the remote machine.

serverStartSecurityPolicyFile.name: serverStartSecurityPolicyFile
serverStartSecurityPolicyFile.description: The security policy file to use when starting this * server. Note that the directory and filename refer to a path on * the remote machine.

serverStartUsername.name: serverStartUsername
serverStartUsername.description: The username to use when booting the server and performing server * health monitoring.

serverStartJavaVendor.name: serverStartJavaVendor
serverStartJavaVendor.description: The Java Vendor value to use when starting this server For example, BEA, Sun, HP etc If the server is part of a cluster and configured for automatic migration across possibly different platforms with different vendors providing the JDKs, then, both JavaVendor and JavaHome should be set in the generated configuration file instead.

snmpAgentTable.name: snmpAgentTable
snmpAgentTable.description: This table represents a snmpAgent in the domain.

snmpAgentIndex.name: snmpAgentIndex
snmpAgentIndex.description: Unique value directed from ObjectName which is used as table index

snmpAgentParent.name: snmpAgentParent
snmpAgentParent.description: BEA-proprietary Parent object's identification, with syntax <type>:<name>

sslTable.name: sslTable
sslTable.description: This table represents a ssl in the domain.

sslIndex.name: sslIndex
sslIndex.description: Unique value directed from ObjectName which is used as table index

sslParent.name: sslParent
sslParent.description: BEA-proprietary Parent object's identification, with syntax <type>:<name>

sslOutboundCertificateValidation.name: sslOutboundCertificateValidation
sslOutboundCertificateValidation.description: Indicates the server certificate validation rules for outbound SSL. This attribute always applies to outbound SSL that is part of WebLogic Server (that is, an Administration Server talking to the Node Manager). It does not apply to application code in the server that is using outbound SSL unless the application code uses a weblogic.security.SSL.ServerTrustManager that is configured to use outbound SSL validation.

sslInboundCertificateValidation.name: sslInboundCertificateValidation
sslInboundCertificateValidation.description: Indicates the client certificate validation rules for inbound SSL. This attribute only applies to ports and network channels using 2-way SSL.

sslCertAuthenticator.name: sslCertAuthenticator
sslCertAuthenticator.description: The name of the Java class that implements the weblogic.security.acl.CertAuthenticator class, which is deprecated in this release of WebLogic Server. This field is for Compatibility security only, and is only used when the Realm Adapter Authentication provider is configured. The weblogic.security.acl.CertAuthenticator class maps the digital certificate of a client to a WebLogic Server user. The class has an authenticate() method that WebLogic Server calls after validating the digital certificate presented by the client.

sslUseServerCerts.name: sslUseServerCerts
sslUseServerCerts.description: Sets whether the client should use the server certificates/key as the client identity when initiating a connection over https.

sslAllowUnencryptedNullCipher.name: sslAllowUnencryptedNullCipher
sslAllowUnencryptedNullCipher.description: Test if the AllowUnEncryptedNullCipher is enabled see setAllowUnencryptedNullCipher(boolean enable) for the NullCipher feature.

startupClassIndex.name: startupClassIndex
startupClassIndex.description: Unique value directed from ObjectName which is used as table index

startupClassParent.name: startupClassParent
startupClassParent.description: BEA-proprietary Parent object's identification, with syntax <type>:<name>

startupClassDeploymentOrder.name: startupClassDeploymentOrder
startupClassDeploymentOrder.description: A priority that the server uses to determine when it deploys an item. The priority is relative to other deployable items of the same type. For example, the server prioritizes and deploys all EJBs before it prioritizes and deploys startup classes. Items with the lowest Deployment Order value are deployed first. There is no guarantee on the order of deployments with equal Deployment Order values. There is no guarantee of ordering across clusters.

startupClassLoadBeforeAppDeployments.name: startupClassLoadBeforeAppDeployments
startupClassLoadBeforeAppDeployments.description: Specifies whether the targeted servers load and run this startup class before activating JMS and JDBC services and before starting deployment for applications and EJBs. If you enable this feature for a startup class, a server loads and runs the startup class before the deployment prepare phase. At this point, JMS and JDBC services are not yet available. (Deployment for applications and EJBs consists of two phases: prepare and activate.) If you do not enable this feature, a server instance loads the startup class after it activates JMS and JDBC services, EJBs, and applications.

startupClassArguments.name: startupClassArguments
startupClassArguments.description: Arguments that a server uses to initialize a class. Separate multiple arguments with a comma. For example: first=MyFirstName,last=MyLastName

startupClassClassName.name: startupClassClassName
startupClassClassName.description: The fully qualified name of a class to load and run. The class must be on the server's classpath. For example, mycompany.mypackage.myclass

startupClassLoadBeforeAppActivation.name: startupClassLoadBeforeAppActivation
startupClassLoadBeforeAppActivation.description: Specifies whether the targeted servers load and run this startup class after activating JMS and JDBC services and before activating applications and EJBs. If you enable this feature for a startup class, a server loads and runs the startup class before the activate phase. At this point, JMS and JDBC services are available. (Deployment for applications and EJBs consists of two phases: prepare and activate.) Enable this feature if the startup class needs to be invoked after JDBC connection pools are available but before the applications are activated and ready to service client requests. If you do not enable this feature, a server instance loads startup classes after it activates JMS and JDBC services, EJBs, and applications.

webAppComponentTable.name: webAppComponentTable
webAppComponentTable.description: This table describes web module of an application.

webAppComponentURI.description: A URI pointing to the application component, usually on the Admin Server.

webAppComponentSingleThreadedServletPool.name: webAppComponentSingleThreadedServletPoolSize
webAppComponentSingleThreadedServletPool.description: The size of the pool used for SingleThreadModle instance pools.

webAppComponentAuthRealmName.name: webAppComponentAuthRealmName
webAppComponentAuthRealmName.description: The Realm in the Basic Authentication HTTP dialog box which pops up on the browsers

webServerIndex.name: webServerIndex
webServerIndex.description: Unique value directed from ObjectName which is used as table index

webServerParent.name: webServerParent
webServerParent.description: BEA-proprietary Parent object's identification, with syntax <type>:<name>

webServerTargets.name: webServerTargets
webServerTargets.description: targets on which this deployment is deployed.

webServerLoggingEnabled.name: webServerLoggingEnabled
webServerLoggingEnabled.description: A boolean value (true Or false). Enables logging of HTTP requests.

webServerLogFileFormat.name: webServerLogFileFormat
webServerLogFileFormat.description: The format of HTTP log file (common or extended)

webServerMaxLogFileSizeKBytes.name: webServerMaxLogFileSizeKBytes
webServerMaxLogFileSizeKBytes.description: maximum access logfile size in K before rotation. 0 means false limit.

webServerLogRotationPeriodMins.name: webServerLogRotationPeriodMins
webServerLogRotationPeriodMins.description: Defines the period in minutes when the access.log will be rotated.

webServerLogFileFlushSecs.name: webServerLogFileFlushSecs
webServerLogFileFlushSecs.description: Frequency (seconds) with which the log file should be flushed

webServerLogRotationTimeBegin.name: webServerLogRotationTimeBegin
webServerLogRotationTimeBegin.description: Defines the date when the first rotation of access.log will begin. The format follows java.text.SimpleDateFormat, MM-dd-yyyy-k:mm:ss

webServerKeepAliveEnabled.name: webServerKeepAliveEnabled
webServerKeepAliveEnabled.description: A boolean value (true Or false). Returns whether or not HTTP keep-alive is enabled

webServerKeepAliveSecs.name: webServerKeepAliveSecs
webServerKeepAliveSecs.description: Number of seconds to maintain HTTP keep-alive before timing out the request.

webServerHttpsKeepAliveSecs.name: webServerHttpsKeepAliveSecs
webServerHttpsKeepAliveSecs.description: Number of seconds to maintain HTTPS keep-alive before timing out the request.

webServerPostTimeoutSecs.name: webServerPostTimeoutSecs
webServerPostTimeoutSecs.description: Timeout (in seconds) for reading HTTP POST data in a servlet request.

webServerMaxPostTimeSecs.name: webServerMaxPostTimeSecs
webServerMaxPostTimeSecs.description: Max Post Time (in seconds) for reading HTTP POST data in a servlet request.

webServerMaxPostSize.name: webServerMaxPostSize
webServerMaxPostSize.description: Max Post Size for reading HTTP POST data in a servlet request.

webServerDefaultWebApp.name: webServerDefaultWebApp
webServerDefaultWebApp.description: Servlet 2.2 Web Application that maps to the default servlet context (where ContextPath = /)

webServerCharsets.name: webServerCharsets
webServerCharsets.description: User defined mapping between internet and Java charset names

webServerURLResource.name: webServerURLResource
webServerURLResource.description: A URL connection factory resource into JNDI

wlecConnectionPoolTable.name: wlecConnectionPoolTable
wlecConnectionPoolTable.description: This table defines a WLEC connection pool.

wlecConnectionPoolIndex.name: wlecConnectionPoolIndex
wlecConnectionPoolIndex.description: Unique value directed from ObjectName which is used as table index

wlecConnectionPoolParent.name: wlecConnectionPoolParent
wlecConnectionPoolParent.description: BEA-proprietary Parent object's identification, with syntax <type>:<name>

wlecConnectionPoolPrimaryAddresses.name: wlecConnectionPoolPrimaryAddresses
wlecConnectionPoolPrimaryAddresses.description: The list of primary ISL addresses.

wlecConnectionPoolFailoverAddresses.name: wlecConnectionPoolFailoverAddresses
wlecConnectionPoolFailoverAddresses.description: The list of failover ISL addresses.

wlecConnectionPoolWLEDomain.name: wlecConnectionPoolWLEDomain
wlecConnectionPoolWLEDomain.description: name of the WebLogic Enterprise domain.

wlecConnectionPoolCertificateAuthenticat.name: wlecConnectionPoolCertificateAuthenticationEnabled
wlecConnectionPoolCertificateAuthenticat.description: boolean value (true Or false). Set to true to enable certificate based authentication

wlecConnectionPoolSecurityContextEnabled.name: wlecConnectionPoolSecurityContextEnabled
wlecConnectionPoolSecurityContextEnabled.description: boolean value (true Or false). Set to true to enable security context propagation.

wlecConnectionPoolTargets.name: wlecConnectionPoolTargets
wlecConnectionPoolTargets.description: targets on which this deployment is deployed.

wlecConnectionPoolDeploymentOrder.name: wlecConnectionPoolDeploymentOrder
wlecConnectionPoolDeploymentOrder.description: A priority that the server uses to determine when it deploys an item. The priority is relative to other deployable items of the same type. For example, the server prioritizes and deploys all EJBs before it prioritizes and deploys startup classes. Items with the lowest Deployment Order value are deployed first. There is no guarantee on the order of deployments with equal Deployment Order values. There is no guarantee of ordering across clusters.

bridgeDestinationTable.name: bridgeDestinationTable
bridgeDestinationTable.description: This table defines a Bridge destination.

bridgeDestinationIndex.description: Unique value directed from ObjectName which is used as table index

bridgeDestinationParent.name: bridgeDestinationParent
bridgeDestinationParent.description: BEA-proprietary Parent object's identification, with syntax <type>:<name>

bridgeDestinationAdapterJNDIName.name: bridgeDestinationAdapterJNDIName
bridgeDestinationAdapterJNDIName.description: Get the JNDI name of the adapter.

messagingBridgeTable.name: messagingBridgeTable
messagingBridgeTable.description: This table defines defines a Messaging Bridge.

messagingBridgeIndex.name: messagingBridgeIndex
messagingBridgeIndex.description: Unique value directed from ObjectName which is used as table index

messagingBridgeParent.name: messagingBridgeParent
messagingBridgeParent.description: BEA-proprietary Parent object's identification, with syntax <type>:<name>

messagingBridgeTargets.name: messagingBridgeTargets
messagingBridgeTargets.description: targets on which this deployment is deployed.

messagingBridgeSourceDestination.name: messagingBridgeSourceDestination
messagingBridgeSourceDestination.description: The source destination defined for the JMS bridge.

messagingBridgeTargetDestination.name: messagingBridgeTargetDestination
messagingBridgeTargetDestination.description: The target destination defined for the JMS bridge.

messagingBridgeSelector.name: messagingBridgeSelector
messagingBridgeSelector.description: The selector defined for the JMS bridge.

messagingBridgeForwardingPolicy.name: messagingBridgeForwardingPolicy
messagingBridgeForwardingPolicy.description: The forwarding policy defined for the JMS bridge.

messagingBridgeScheduleTime.name: messagingBridgeScheduleTime
messagingBridgeScheduleTime.description: The schedule time defined for the JMS bridge.

messagingBridgeQualityOfService.name: messagingBridgeQualityOfService
messagingBridgeQualityOfService.description: The quality of service defined for the JMS bridge.

messagingBridgeIdleTimeMaximum.name: messagingBridgeIdleTimeMaximum
messagingBridgeIdleTimeMaximum.description: The maximum wait time defined for the JMS bridge.

messagingBridgeTransactionTimeout.name: messagingBridgeTransactionTimeout
messagingBridgeTransactionTimeout.description: The transaction timeout defined for the JMS bridge.

messagingBridgeAsyncDisabled.name: messagingBridgeAsyncDisabled
messagingBridgeAsyncDisabled.description: Return true, if the Async is Disabled.

messagingBridgeDurabilityEnabled.name: messagingBridgeDurabilityEnabled
messagingBridgeDurabilityEnabled.description: Specifies whether or not the messaging bridge allows durable messages. When enabled and the source destination is a JMS topic, a messaging bridge instance uses a durable subscription to ensure that no messages are lost in the event of a failure. DurabilityEnabled ignored if the source destination is a JMS queue. When enabled and the source destination uses durable subscriptions, the source JMS implementation saves messages that are sent when a messaging bridge instance is not running. When the bridge instance is restarted, these messages are forwarded to the target destination. The administrator can choose not to be durable. When not enabled, messages that are sent to the source JMS implementation while the bridge instance is down cannot be forwarded to the target destination.

messagingBridgeReconnectDelayMinimum.name: messagingBridgeReconnectDelayMinimum
messagingBridgeReconnectDelayMinimum.description: The minimum amount of time, in seconds, that a messaging bridge instance waits before it tries to reconnect to the source or target destination after a failure. Use with ReconnectDelayMaximum and ReconnectDelayIncrease. After the first failure to connect to a destination, the bridge instance waits for the number of seconds defined by ReconnectDelayMinimum. Each time a reconnect attempt fails, the bridge instance increases its waiting time by the number of seconds defined by ReconnectDelayIncrease. The maximum delay time is defined by ReconnectDelayMaximum. Once the waiting time is increased to the maximum value, the bridge instance stops increase its waiting time. Once the bridge instance successfully connects to the destination, the bridge instance resets its waiting time to the initial value defined by ReconnectDelayMinimum.

messagingBridgePreserveMsgProperty.name: messagingBridgePreserveMsgProperty
messagingBridgePreserveMsgProperty.description: Specifies if message properties are preserved when messages are forwarded by a bridge instance. If the target bridge destination is on wls 9.0 or higher, the following message properties are preserved: message ID message timestamp user ID delivery mode priority expiration time redelivery limit unit of order name If the target bridge destination is on wls between 6.0 and 8.1 or on a foreign JMS server, the following message properties are preserved: delivery mode priority expiration time If the target bridge destination is on wls 5.1 or older, no properties are preserved.

messagingBridgeBatchSize.name: messagingBridgeBatchSize
messagingBridgeBatchSize.description: The number of messages that are processed within one transaction. Batch Size only applies to a messaging bridge instance forwarding messages in synchronous mode and has a QOS (quality of service) that requires two-phase transactions.

messagingBridgeReconnectDelayMaximum.name: messagingBridgeReconnectDelayMaximum
messagingBridgeReconnectDelayMaximum.description: The longest time, in seconds, that a messaging bridge instance waits between one failed attempt to connect to the source or target, and the next retry. Use with ReconnectDelayMinimum and ReconnectDelayIncrease. After the first failure to connect to a destination, a bridge instance waits for the number of seconds defined by ReconnectDelayMinimum. Each time a reconnect attempt fails, the bridge instance increases its waiting time by the number of seconds defined by ReconnectDelayIncrease. The maximum delay time is defined by ReconnectDelayMaximum. Once the waiting time is increased to the maximum value, the bridge instance stops increase its waiting time. Once the bridge instance successfully connects to the destination, the bridge instance resets its waiting time to the initial value defined by ReconnectDelayMinimum.

messagingBridgeDeploymentOrder.name: messagingBridgeDeploymentOrder
messagingBridgeDeploymentOrder.description: A priority that the server uses to determine when it deploys an item. The priority is relative to other deployable items of the same type. For example, the server prioritizes and deploys all EJBs before it prioritizes and deploys startup classes. Items with the lowest Deployment Order value are deployed first. There is no guarantee on the order of deployments with equal Deployment Order values. There is no guarantee of ordering across clusters.

messagingBridgeAsyncEnabled.name: messagingBridgeAsyncEnabled
messagingBridgeAsyncEnabled.description: Specifies if a messaging bridge instance forwards in asynchronous messaging mode. AsyncEnabled only applies to messaging bridge instances whose source destination supports asynchronous receiving. Messaging bridges instances that forward in asynchronous mode are driven by the source destination. A messaging bridge instance listens for messages and forwards them as they arrive. When AsyncEnabled is not selected, a bridge instance is forced to work in synchronous mode, even if the source supports asynchronous receiving. Note: For a messaging bridge instance with a QOS of Exactly-once to work in asynchronous mode, the source destination has to support the MDBTransaction interface. Otherwise, the bridge automatically switches to synchronous mode if it detects that MDBTransaction is not supported by the source destination.

messagingBridgeBatchInterval.name: messagingBridgeBatchInterval
messagingBridgeBatchInterval.description: The maximum amount of time, in milliseconds, that a messaging bridge instance waits before sending a batch of messages in one transaction, regardless of whether the Batch Size has been reached or not. Only applies to a messaging bridge instance forwarding messages in synchronous mode and has a QOS (quality of service) that requires two-phase transactions. The default value of -1 indicates that the bridge instance waits until the number of messages reaches the Batch Size before it completes a transaction.

messagingBridgeStarted.name: messagingBridgeStarted
messagingBridgeStarted.description: Specifies the initial operating state of a targetted messaging bridge instance. If enabled, the messaging bridge instance forwards messages (running). If not enabled, the messaging bridge instance does not forward messages (temporarily stopped). After a messaging bridge has started forwarding messages (running), use Started to temporarily suspend an active messaging bridge instance or restart an stopped messaging bridge instance. Select the Started checkbox to start a messaging bridge instance that has been temporarily stopped. Clear the Started checkbox to temporarily stop a messaging bridge instance that was running. This value does not indicate the run-time state of a messaging bridge instance.

messagingBridgeReconnectDelayIncrease.name: messagingBridgeReconnectDelayIncrease
messagingBridgeReconnectDelayIncrease.description: The incremental delay time, in seconds, that a messaging bridge instance increases its waiting time between one failed reconnection attempt and the next retry. Use with ReconnectDelayMinimum and ReconnectDelayMaximum. After the first failure to connect to a destination, the bridge instance waits for the number of seconds defined by ReconnectDelayMinimum. Each time a reconnect attempt fails, the bridge instance increases its waiting time by the number of seconds defined by ReconnectDelayIncrease. The maximum delay time is defined by ReconnectDelayMaximum. Once the waiting time is increased to the maximum value, the bridge instance stops increase its waiting time. Once the bridge instance successfully connects to the destination, the bridge instance resets its waiting time to the initial value defined by ReconnectDelayMinimum.

virtualHostTable.name: virtualHostTable
virtualHostTable.description: This table epresents the configuration of virtual web server within a WebLogic server. Note that a server may define multiple web servers to support virtual hosts.

virtualHostIndex.name: virtualHostIndex
virtualHostIndex.description: Unique value directed from ObjectName which is used as table index

virtualHostParent.name: virtualHostParent
virtualHostParent.description: BEA-proprietary Parent object's identification, with syntax <type>:<name>

virtualHostTargets.name: virtualHostTargets
virtualHostTargets.description: targets on which this deployment is deployed.

virtualHostLoggingEnabled.name: virtualHostLoggingEnabled
virtualHostLoggingEnabled.description: A boolean value (true Or false). Enables logging of HTTP requests.

virtualHostLogFileFormat.name: virtualHostLogFileFormat
virtualHostLogFileFormat.description: Defines the format of HTTP log file (common or extended)

virtualHostLogFileName.name: virtualHostLogFileName
virtualHostLogFileName.description: Sets the HTTP request log file

virtualHostLogFileBufferKBytes.name: virtualHostLogFileBufferKBytes
virtualHostLogFileBufferKBytes.description: Sets HTTP request log buffer size

virtualHostMaxLogFileSizeKBytes.name: virtualHostMaxLogFileSizeKBytes
virtualHostMaxLogFileSizeKBytes.description: Set maximum access logfile size in K before rotation. 0 means false limit.

virtualHostLogRotationType.name: virtualHostLogRotationType
virtualHostLogRotationType.description: Defines how the HTTP log file is rotated [size|date].

virtualHostLogRotationPeriodMins.name: virtualHostLogRotationPeriodMins
virtualHostLogRotationPeriodMins.description: Defines the period in minutes when the access.log will be rotated.

virtualHostLogFileFlushSecs.name: virtualHostLogFileFlushSecs
virtualHostLogFileFlushSecs.description: Frequency (seconds) with which the log file should be flushed

virtualHostLogRotationTimeBegin.name: virtualHostLogRotationTimeBegin
virtualHostLogRotationTimeBegin.description: Defines the date when the first rotation of access.log will begin. The format follows java.text.SimpleDateFormat, MM-dd-yyyy-k:mm:ss

virtualHostKeepAliveEnabled.name: virtualHostKeepAliveEnabled
virtualHostKeepAliveEnabled.description: A boolean value (true Or false). Returns whether or not HTTP keep-alive is enabled

virtualHostKeepAliveSecs.name: virtualHostKeepAliveSecs
virtualHostKeepAliveSecs.description: Number of seconds to maintain HTTP keep-alive before timing out the request.

virtualHostHttpsKeepAliveSecs.name: virtualHostHttpsKeepAliveSecs
virtualHostHttpsKeepAliveSecs.description: Number of seconds to maintain HTTPS keep-alive before timing out the request.

virtualHostPostTimeoutSecs.name: virtualHostPostTimeoutSecs
virtualHostPostTimeoutSecs.description: Timeout (in seconds) for reading HTTP POST data in a servlet request.

virtualHostMaxPostTimeSecs.name: virtualHostMaxPostTimeSecs
virtualHostMaxPostTimeSecs.description: Max Post Time (in seconds) for reading HTTP POST data in a servlet request.

virtualHostMaxPostSize.name: virtualHostMaxPostSize
virtualHostMaxPostSize.description: Max Post Size for reading HTTP POST data in a servlet request.

virtualHostDefaultWebApp.name: virtualHostDefaultWebApp
virtualHostDefaultWebApp.description: Servlet 2.2 Web Application that maps to the default servlet context (where ContextPath = /)

virtualHostCharsets.name: virtualHostCharsets
virtualHostCharsets.description: User defined mapping between internet and Java charset names

virtualHostURLResource.name: virtualHostURLResource
virtualHostURLResource.description: A URL connection factory resource into JNDI

virtualHostVirtualHostNames.name: virtualHostVirtualHostNames
virtualHostVirtualHostNames.description: The host name for which this web server will serve requests.

virtualHostFrontendHTTPPort.name: virtualHostFrontendHTTPPort
virtualHostFrontendHTTPPort.description: The name of the HTTP port to which all redirected URLs will be sent. If specified, WebLogic Server will use this value rather than the one in the HOST header. Sets the frontendHTTPPort Provides a method to ensure that the webapp will always have the correct PORT information, even when the request is coming through a firewall or a proxy. If this parameter is configured, the HOST header will be ignored and the information in this parameter will be used in its place.

virtualHostAuthCookieEnabled.name: virtualHostAuthCookieEnabled
virtualHostAuthCookieEnabled.description: Whether authcookie feature is enabled or not.

virtualHostSingleSignonDisabled.name: virtualHostSingleSignonDisabled
virtualHostSingleSignonDisabled.description: Indicates whether the singleSignonDisabled attribute is enabled

virtualHostChunkedTransferDisabled.name: virtualHostChunkedTransferDisabled
virtualHostChunkedTransferDisabled.description: Indicates whether the use of Chunk Transfer-Encoding in HTTP/1.1 is enabled.

virtualHostAcceptContextPathInGetRealPat.name: virtualHostAcceptContextPathInGetRealPath
virtualHostAcceptContextPathInGetRealPat.description: Indicates whether this server allows the inclusion of the context path in the virtual path to context.getRealPath(). (If checked, you cannot use sub directories with the same name as contextPath). This is a compatibility switch that will be deprecated 9.0.0.0 in future releases. Gets the acceptContextPathInGetRealPath attribute of the WebServerMBean object

virtualHostOverloadResponseCode.name: virtualHostOverloadResponseCode
virtualHostOverloadResponseCode.description: Get the response code to be used when an application is overloaded. An application can get overloaded when the number of pending requests has reached the max capacity specified in the WorkManager or when the server is low on memory. The low memory condition is determined using {@link OverloadProtectionMBean#getFreeMemoryPercentLowThreshold()}.

virtualHostDeploymentOrder.name: virtualHostDeploymentOrder
virtualHostDeploymentOrder.description: A priority that the server uses to determine when it deploys an item. The priority is relative to other deployable items of the same type. For example, the server prioritizes and deploys all EJBs before it prioritizes and deploys startup classes. Items with the lowest Deployment Order value are deployed first. There is no guarantee on the order of deployments with equal Deployment Order values. There is no guarantee of ordering across clusters.

virtualHostNetworkAccessPoint.name: virtualHostNetworkAccessPoint
virtualHostNetworkAccessPoint.description: The dedicated server channel name (NetworkAccessPoint) for which this virtual host will serve http request. If the NetworkAccessPoint for a given http request doesn't match any virtual host's NetworkAccessPoint, incoming HOST header will be matched with the VirtualHostNames in order to resolve the right virtual host.

virtualHostSendServerHeaderEnabled.name: virtualHostSendServerHeaderEnabled
virtualHostSendServerHeaderEnabled.description: Indicates whether this server name is sent with the HTTP response. (This is useful for wireless applications where there is limited space for headers.) Indicates whether this server instance includes its name and WebLogic Server version number in HTTP response headers.

virtualHostFrontendHost.name: virtualHostFrontendHost
virtualHostFrontendHost.description: The name of the host to which all redirected URLs will be sent. If specified, WebLogic Server will use this value rather than the one in the HOST header. Sets the HTTP frontendHost Provides a method to ensure that the webapp will always have the correct HOST information, even when the request is coming through a firewall or a proxy. If this parameter is configured, the HOST header will be ignored and the information in this parameter will be used in its place.

virtualHostWriteChunkBytes.name: virtualHostWriteChunkBytes
virtualHostWriteChunkBytes.description: The default size of the blocks to be written to the network layer. Gets the writeChunkBytes attribute of the WebServerMBean object

virtualHostFrontendHTTPSPort.name: virtualHostFrontendHTTPSPort
virtualHostFrontendHTTPSPort.description: The name of the secure HTTP port to which all redirected URLs will be sent. If specified, WebLogic Server will use this value rather than the one in the HOST header. Sets the frontendHTTPSPort Provides a method to ensure that the webapp will always have the correct PORT information, even when the request is coming through a firewall or a proxy. If this parameter is configured, the HOST header will be ignored and the information in this parameter will be used in its place.

virtualHostUseHighestCompatibleHTTPVersi.name: virtualHostUseHighestCompatibleHTTPVersion
virtualHostUseHighestCompatibleHTTPVersi.description: Enables use of the highest compatible HTTP protocol version-string in the response. E.g. HTTP spec suggests that HTTP/1.1 version-string should be used in response to a request using HTTP/1.0. This does not necessarily affect the response format.

virtualHostDefaultWebAppContextRoot.name: virtualHostDefaultWebAppContextRoot
virtualHostDefaultWebAppContextRoot.description: Returns the original context-root for the default Web application for this Web server. Alternatively, you can use the context-root attributes in application.xml or weblogic.xml to set a default Web application. The context-root for a default Web application is /. If '' (empty string) is specified, the Web server defaults to /.

xmlEntityCacheTable.name: xmlEntityCacheTable
xmlEntityCacheTable.description: Configures the behavior of JAXP (Java API for XML Parsing) in the server.

xmlEntityCacheIndex.name: xmlEntityCacheIndex
xmlEntityCacheIndex.description: Unique value directed from ObjectName which is used as table index

xmlEntityCacheParent.name: xmlEntityCacheParent
xmlEntityCacheParent.description: BEA-proprietary Parent object's identification, with syntax <type>:<name>

xmlEntityCacheCacheMemorySize.name: xmlEntityCacheCacheMemorySize
xmlEntityCacheCacheMemorySize.description: The memory size in KBytes of the cache.

xmlEntityCacheCacheDiskSize.name: xmlEntityCacheCacheDiskSize
xmlEntityCacheCacheDiskSize.description: The disk size in MBytes of the cache.

xmlEntityCacheCacheTimeoutInterval.name: xmlEntityCacheCacheTimeoutInterval
xmlEntityCacheCacheTimeoutInterval.description: Return the default timeout interval in seconds for the cache.

xmlEntityCacheCacheLocation.name: xmlEntityCacheCacheLocation
xmlEntityCacheCacheLocation.description: Provides the path name for the persistent cache files.

xmlEntityCacheMaxSize.name: xmlEntityCacheMaxSize
xmlEntityCacheMaxSize.description: Provides the maximum number of entries that can be stored in the cache at any given time.

xmlEntitySpecRegistryTable.name: xmlEntitySpecRegistryTable
xmlEntitySpecRegistryTable.description: This is an entry in the XML registry. An XML registry entry is configuration information associated with a particular XML document type. Entries accessed through this interface are used to specify a local instance for a remote entity reference.

xmlEntitySpecRegistryIndex.name: xmlEntitySpecRegistryIndex
xmlEntitySpecRegistryIndex.description: Unique value directed from ObjectName which is used as table index

xmlEntitySpecRegistryParent.name: xmlEntitySpecRegistryParent
xmlEntitySpecRegistryParent.description: BEA-proprietary Parent object's identification, with syntax <type>:<name>

xmlEntitySpecRegistryPublicId.name: xmlEntitySpecRegistryPublicId
xmlEntitySpecRegistryPublicId.description: The public id of the document type represented by this registry entry.

xmlEntitySpecRegistrySystemId.name: xmlEntitySpecRegistrySystemId
xmlEntitySpecRegistrySystemId.description: The system id of the document type represented by this registry entry.

xmlEntitySpecRegistryEntityURI.name: xmlEntitySpecRegistryEntityURI
xmlEntitySpecRegistryEntityURI.description: Return the location of a local copy of an external entity (e.g., a DTD) that is associated with this registry entry.

xmlEntitySpecRegistryWhenToCache.name: xmlEntitySpecRegistryWhenToCache
xmlEntitySpecRegistryWhenToCache.description: whether to cache this item as soon as possible or wait until it is referenced.

xmlEntitySpecRegistryCacheTimeoutInterva.name: xmlEntitySpecRegistryCacheTimeoutInterval
xmlEntitySpecRegistryCacheTimeoutInterva.description: Return the default timeout interval in seconds for the cache. ???delgation

xmlEntitySpecRegistryHandleEntityInvalid.name: xmlEntitySpecRegistryHandleEntityInvalidation
xmlEntitySpecRegistryHandleEntityInvalid.description: Whether cached DTD/schema is invalidated when parsing error is encountered.

xmlParserSelectRegistryTable.name: xmlParserSelectRegistryTable
xmlParserSelectRegistryTable.description: This is an entry in the XML registry. An XML registry entry is configuration information associated with a particular XML document type. Entries accessed through this interface are used to specify a Sax parser and/or document builder of the provided document type.

xmlParserSelectRegistryIndex.name: xmlParserSelectRegistryIndex
xmlParserSelectRegistryIndex.description: Unique value directed from ObjectName which is used as table index

xmlParserSelectRegistryParent.name: xmlParserSelectRegistryParent
xmlParserSelectRegistryParent.description: BEA-proprietary Parent object's identification, with syntax <type>:<name>

xmlParserSelectRegistryPublicId.name: xmlParserSelectRegistryPublicId
xmlParserSelectRegistryPublicId.description: The public id of the document type represented by this registry entry.

xmlParserSelectRegistrySystemId.name: xmlParserSelectRegistrySystemId
xmlParserSelectRegistrySystemId.description: The system id of the document type represented by this registry entry.

xmlParserSelectRegistryRootElementTag.name: xmlParserSelectRegistryRootElementTag
xmlParserSelectRegistryRootElementTag.description: The tag name of the document root element of the document type represented by this registry entry.

xmlParserSelectRegistryDocumentBuilderFa.name: xmlParserSelectRegistryDocumentBuilderFactory
xmlParserSelectRegistryDocumentBuilderFa.description: Return the class name of the DocumentBuilderFactory that is associated with the registry entry.

xmlParserSelectRegistrySAXParserFactory.name: xmlParserSelectRegistrySAXParserFactory
xmlParserSelectRegistrySAXParserFactory.description: Return the class name of the SAXParserFactory that is associated with the registry entry.

xmlParserSelectRegistryTransformerFactor.name: xmlParserSelectRegistryTransformerFactory
xmlParserSelectRegistryTransformerFactor.description: Return the class name of the default TransformerFactory.

xmlRegistryTable.name: xmlRegistryTable
xmlRegistryTable.description: Configure the behavior of JAXP (Java API for XML Parsing) in the server.

xmlRegistryIndex.name: xmlRegistryIndex
xmlRegistryIndex.description: Unique value directed from ObjectName which is used as table index

xmlRegistryParent.name: xmlRegistryParent
xmlRegistryParent.description: BEA-proprietary Parent object's identification, with syntax <type>:<name>

xmlRegistryRegistryEntries.name: xmlRegistryRegistryEntries
xmlRegistryRegistryEntries.description: Return the set of registry entries.

xmlRegistryParserSelectRegistryEntries.name: xmlRegistryParserSelectRegistryEntries
xmlRegistryParserSelectRegistryEntries.description: Return the set of ParserSelect registry entries.

xmlRegistryEntitySpecRegistryEntries.name: xmlRegistryEntitySpecRegistryEntries
xmlRegistryEntitySpecRegistryEntries.description: Return the set of EntitySpec registry entries.

xmlRegistryDocumentBuilderFactory.name: xmlRegistryDocumentBuilderFactory
xmlRegistryDocumentBuilderFactory.description: Return the class name of the DocumentBuilderFactory that is associated with the registry entry.

xmlRegistrySAXParserFactory.name: xmlRegistrySAXParserFactory
xmlRegistrySAXParserFactory.description: Return the class name of the SAXParserFactory that is associated with the registry entry.

xmlRegistryTransformerFactory.name: xmlRegistryTransformerFactory
xmlRegistryTransformerFactory.description: The class name of the default TransformerFactory.

xmlRegistryWhenToCache.name: xmlRegistryWhenToCache
xmlRegistryWhenToCache.description: Whether to cache items as soon as possible or wait until referenced.

xmlRegistryHandleEntityInvalidation.name: xmlRegistryHandleEntityInvalidation
xmlRegistryHandleEntityInvalidation.description: Whether cached DTD/schema is invalidated when parsing error is encountered.

wtctBridgeGlobalTable.name: wtctBridgeGlobalTable
wtctBridgeGlobalTable.description: This table represents a wtctBridgeGlobal in the domain.

wtctBridgeGlobalIndex.name: wtctBridgeGlobalIndex
wtctBridgeGlobalIndex.description: Unique value directed from ObjectName which is used as table index

wtctBridgeGlobalParent.name: wtctBridgeGlobalParent
wtctBridgeGlobalParent.description: BEA-proprietary Parent object's identification, with syntax <type>:<name>

wtctBridgeGlobalAllowNonStandardTypes.name: wtctBridgeGlobalAllowNonStandardTypes
wtctBridgeGlobalAllowNonStandardTypes.description: Defines a flag used to specify if non-standard data types are allowed to * pass through the tBridge. Standard types are: type ASCII text (TextMessage, STRING), * or type BLOB (BytesMessage, CARRAY).

wtctBridgeGlobalDefaultReplyDeliveryMode.name: wtctBridgeGlobalDefaultReplyDeliveryMode
wtctBridgeGlobalDefaultReplyDeliveryMode.description: Defines the reply delivery mode to associate with a message when placing messages onto the target location

wtctBridgeGlobalDeliveryModeOverride.name: wtctBridgeGlobalDeliveryModeOverride
wtctBridgeGlobalDeliveryModeOverride.description: Defines the delivery mode to use when placing messages onto the target location.

wtctBridgeGlobalJmsFactory.name: wtctBridgeGlobalJmsFactory
wtctBridgeGlobalJmsFactory.description: Defines the name of the JMS connection factory.

wtctBridgeGlobalJmsToTuxPriorityMap.name: wtctBridgeGlobalJmsToTuxPriorityMap
wtctBridgeGlobalJmsToTuxPriorityMap.description: Defines the mapping of priorities from JMS to Tuxedo.

wtctBridgeGlobalJndiFactory.name: wtctBridgeGlobalJndiFactory
wtctBridgeGlobalJndiFactory.description: Defines the name of the JNDI lookup factory.

wtctBridgeGlobalRetries.name: wtctBridgeGlobalRetries
wtctBridgeGlobalRetries.description: Defines the number of attempts to redirect a message before putting the message in the specified error location and logging an error.

wtctBridgeGlobalRetryDelay.name: wtctBridgeGlobalRetryDelay
wtctBridgeGlobalRetryDelay.description: Defines the minimum amount of time (milliseconds) to wait before redirecting a message after a failure. During this time, no other messages are redirected from the thread. Other threads may continue to redirect messages.

wtctBridgeGlobalTimeout.name: wtctBridgeGlobalTimeout
wtctBridgeGlobalTimeout.description: Defines the effective length of a timeout for an entire redirection (seconds) when placing a message on the target location. 0 indicates an infinite wait.

wtctBridgeGlobalTransactional.name: wtctBridgeGlobalTransactional
wtctBridgeGlobalTransactional.description: Defines a flag that specifies the use of transactions when retrieving messages from a source location and when placing messages on a target location.

wtctBridgeGlobalTuxErrorQueue.name: wtctBridgeGlobalTuxErrorQueue
wtctBridgeGlobalTuxErrorQueue.description: Defines the name of the Tuxedo queue used to store a message that connot be redirected to a Tuxedo/Q source queue. This queue is in the same queue space as the source queue.

wtctBridgeGlobalTuxFactory.name: wtctBridgeGlobalTuxFactory
wtctBridgeGlobalTuxFactory.description: Defines the name of the Tuxedo connection factory.

wtctBridgeGlobalTuxToJmsPriorityMap.name: wtctBridgeGlobalTuxToJmsPriorityMap
wtctBridgeGlobalTuxToJmsPriorityMap.description: Defines the mapping of priorities to map from Tuxedo to JMS.

wtctBridgeGlobalUserId.name: wtctBridgeGlobalUserId
wtctBridgeGlobalUserId.description: Defines a user identity for all messages handled by the tBridge for ACL checks when security is configured.

wtctBridgeGlobalWlsErrorDestination.name: wtctBridgeGlobalWlsErrorDestination
wtctBridgeGlobalWlsErrorDestination.description: Defines the name of the location used to store WebLogic Server JMS messages when a message cannot be redirected.

wtcExportTable.name: wtcExportTable
wtcExportTable.description: This table represents a wtcExport in the domain.

wtcExportIndex.name: wtcExportIndex
wtcExportIndex.description: Unique value directed from ObjectName which is used as table index

wtcExportParent.name: wtcExportParent
wtcExportParent.description: BEA-proprietary Parent object's identification, with syntax <type>:<name>

wtcExportEJBName.name: wtcExportEJBName
wtcExportEJBName.description: Defines the name of the local access point that exports the service.

wtcExportLocalAccessPoint.name: wtcExportLocalAccessPoint
wtcExportLocalAccessPoint.description: Defines the name of the local access point that exports the service.

wtcExportRemoteName.name: wtcExportRemoteName
wtcExportRemoteName.description: Defines the remote name of the service. If not specified, the ResourceName attribute is used.

wtcExportResourceName.name: wtcExportResourceName
wtcExportResourceName.description: Defines the name used to identify an exported service.

wtcImportTable.name: wtcImportTable
wtcImportTable.description: This table represents a wtcImport in the domain.

wtcImportIndex.name: wtcImportIndex
wtcImportIndex.description: Unique value directed from ObjectName which is used as table index

wtcImportParent.name: wtcImportParent
wtcImportParent.description: BEA-proprietary Parent object's identification, with syntax <type>:<name>

wtcImportLocalAccessPoint.name: wtcImportLocalAccessPoint
wtcImportLocalAccessPoint.description: The certificate type used for secure communications with the wtcImport .

wtcImportResourceName.name: wtcImportResourceName
wtcImportResourceName.description: The port on which wtcImport listens for connections.

wtcLocalTuxDomTable.name: wtcLocalTuxDomTable
wtcLocalTuxDomTable.description: This table represents a wtcLocalTuxDom in the domain.

wtcLocalTuxDomIndex.name: wtcLocalTuxDomIndex
wtcLocalTuxDomIndex.description: Unique value directed from ObjectName which is used as table index

wtcLocalTuxDomParent.name: wtcLocalTuxDomParent
wtcLocalTuxDomParent.description: BEA-proprietary Parent object's identification, with syntax <type>:<name>

wtcLocalTuxDomAccessPoint.name: wtcLocalTuxDomAccessPoint
wtcLocalTuxDomAccessPoint.description: Defines a unique name within the scope of MBean types WTCLocalTuxDom and WTCRemoteTuxDom used to identify the access point or domain.

wtcLocalTuxDomAccessPointId.name: wtcLocalTuxDomAccessPointId
wtcLocalTuxDomAccessPointId.description: Defines the domain access point identifier. This identifier is a unique name across all local and remote domain access points.

wtcLocalTuxDomBlockTime.name: wtcLocalTuxDomBlockTime
wtcLocalTuxDomBlockTime.description: Defines the maximum wait time (seconds) allowed for a blocking call.

wtcLocalTuxDomCmpLimit.name: wtcLocalTuxDomCmpLimit
wtcLocalTuxDomCmpLimit.description: Defines the compression threshold used when sending data to a remote domain. Application buffers larger than this size are compressed.

wtcLocalTuxDomConnectionPolicy.name: wtcLocalTuxDomConnectionPolicy
wtcLocalTuxDomConnectionPolicy.description: Defines the conditions under which a local domain tries to establish a connection to a remote domain.

wtcLocalTuxDomConnPrincipalName.name: wtcLocalTuxDomConnPrincipalName
wtcLocalTuxDomConnPrincipalName.description: Defines the principal name used to verify the identity of this domain when establishing a connection to another domain.

wtcLocalTuxDomInteroperate.name: wtcLocalTuxDomInteroperate
wtcLocalTuxDomInteroperate.description: Specifies whether the local domain interoperates with remote domains that are based upon Tuxedo release 6.5. If Yes, the local domain interoperates with a Tuxedo 6.5 domain.

wtcLocalTuxDomMaxEncryptBits.name: wtcLocalTuxDomMaxEncryptBits
wtcLocalTuxDomMaxEncryptBits.description: Defines the maximum encryption key length (in bits) used when establishing a network connection for a local domain.

wtcLocalTuxDomMaxRetries.name: wtcLocalTuxDomMaxRetries
wtcLocalTuxDomMaxRetries.description: Defines the number of times that a domain gateway tries to establish connections to remote domain access points. Use only when Connection Policy is set to ON_STARTUP.

wtcLocalTuxDomMinEncryptBits.name: wtcLocalTuxDomMinEncryptBits
wtcLocalTuxDomMinEncryptBits.description: Defines the minimum encryption key length (in bits) used when establishing a network connection for a local domain.

wtcLocalTuxDomNWAddr.name: wtcLocalTuxDomNWAddr
wtcLocalTuxDomNWAddr.description: Defines the network address of the local domain gateway. Specify the TCP/IP address in one of the following formats

wtcLocalTuxDomRetryInterval.name: wtcLocalTuxDomRetryInterval
wtcLocalTuxDomRetryInterval.description: Defines the number of seconds between automatic attempts to establish a connection to remote domain access points. Use only when Connection Policy is set to ON_STARTUP.

wtcLocalTuxDomSecurity.name: wtcLocalTuxDomSecurity
wtcLocalTuxDomSecurity.description: Defines the type of application security enforced.

wtcLocalTuxDomKeyStoresLocation.name: wtcLocalTuxDomKeyStoresLocation
wtcLocalTuxDomKeyStoresLocation.description: Which configuration rules should be used for finding this Local Tuxedo access point's identity and trust keystores?

wtcLocalTuxDomSSLRenegotiation.name: wtcLocalTuxDomSSLRenegotiation
wtcLocalTuxDomSSLRenegotiation.description: The amount of time between session re-negotiations when the SSL protocol is in use. Range of values: Between 0 and a positive 32-bit integer.

wtcLocalTuxDomUseSSL.name: wtcLocalTuxDomUseSSL
wtcLocalTuxDomUseSSL.description: Return value that tells whether connection performed or out of or accepted from this Local Tuxedo access point will use SSL on top of its transport layer.

wtcLocalTuxDomKeepAliveWait.name: wtcLocalTuxDomKeepAliveWait
wtcLocalTuxDomKeepAliveWait.description: Return value that tells whether this local Tuxedo access point requires the acknowledgement of Application Level Keep Alive, and how long it will wait without receiving acknowledgement before declare the connection is inaccessable.

wtcLocalTuxDomTrustKeyStoreFileName.name: wtcLocalTuxDomTrustKeyStoreFileName
wtcLocalTuxDomTrustKeyStoreFileName.description: The path and file name of the trust keystore. The path name must either be absolute or relative to where the server was booted. This file name is only used if KeyStores is 'Custom Stores'.

wtcLocalTuxDomKeepAlive.name: wtcLocalTuxDomKeepAlive
wtcLocalTuxDomKeepAlive.description: Return value tells whether this local Tuxedo access point is configured with Application Level Keep Alive, and it maximum idle time value before wait timer start ticking.

wtcLocalTuxDomPrivateKeyAlias.name: wtcLocalTuxDomPrivateKeyAlias
wtcLocalTuxDomPrivateKeyAlias.description: The string alias used to store and retrieve the Local Tuxedo access point's private key in the keystore. This private key is associated with the Local Tuxedo access point's digital certificate.

wtcLocalTuxDomIdentityKeyStoreFileName.name: wtcLocalTuxDomIdentityKeyStoreFileName
wtcLocalTuxDomIdentityKeyStoreFileName.description: The path and file name of the identity keystore. The path name must either be absolute or relative to where the server was booted. The identity key store file name is only used if KeystoreLocation is 'Custom Stores'.

wtcRemoteTuxDomTable.name: wtcRemoteTuxDomTable
wtcRemoteTuxDomTable.description: This table represents a wtcRemoteTuxDom in the domain.

wtcRemoteTuxDomIndex.name: wtcRemoteTuxDomIndex
wtcRemoteTuxDomIndex.description: Unique value directed from ObjectName which is used as table index

wtcRemoteTuxDomParent.name: wtcRemoteTuxDomParent
wtcRemoteTuxDomParent.description: BEA-proprietary Parent object's identification, with syntax <type>:<name>

wtcRemoteTuxDomAccessPoint.name: wtcRemoteTuxDomAccessPoint
wtcRemoteTuxDomAccessPoint.description: Defines a unique name within the scope of MBean types WTCLocalTuxDom and WTCRemoteTuxDom used to identify the access point or domain.

wtcRemoteTuxDomAccessPointId.name: wtcRemoteTuxDomAccessPointId
wtcRemoteTuxDomAccessPointId.description: Defines the domain access point identifier. This identifier is unique across all local and remote domain access points.

wtcRemoteTuxDomAclPolicy.name: wtcRemoteTuxDomAclPolicy
wtcRemoteTuxDomAclPolicy.description: Defines the inbound access control list (ACL) policy toward requests from a remote domain.

wtcRemoteTuxDomCmpLimit.name: wtcRemoteTuxDomCmpLimit
wtcRemoteTuxDomCmpLimit.description: Defines the compression threshold used when sending data to a remote domain. Application buffers larger than this size are compressed.

wtcRemoteTuxDomConnectionPolicy.name: wtcRemoteTuxDomConnectionPolicy
wtcRemoteTuxDomConnectionPolicy.description: Defines the conditions under which a local domain tries to establish a connection to a remote domain.

wtcRemoteTuxDomConnPrincipalName.name: wtcRemoteTuxDomConnPrincipalName
wtcRemoteTuxDomConnPrincipalName.description: Defines the principal name used to verify the identity of this domain when establishing a connection to another domain.

wtcRemoteTuxDomCredentialPolicy.name: wtcRemoteTuxDomCredentialPolicy
wtcRemoteTuxDomCredentialPolicy.description: Defines the outbound access control list (ACL) policy toward requests to a remote domain.

wtcRemoteTuxDomMaxEncryptBits.name: wtcRemoteTuxDomMaxEncryptBits
wtcRemoteTuxDomMaxEncryptBits.description: Defines the maximum encryption key length (in bits) used when establishing a network connection for a local domain.

wtcRemoteTuxDomMaxRetries.name: wtcRemoteTuxDomMaxRetries
wtcRemoteTuxDomMaxRetries.description: Defines the number of times that a domain gateway tries to establish connections to remote domain access points. Use only when Connection Policy is set to ON_STARTUP.

wtcRemoteTuxDomMinEncryptBits.name: wtcRemoteTuxDomMinEncryptBits
wtcRemoteTuxDomMinEncryptBits.description: Defines the minimum encryption key length (in bits) used when establishing a network connection for a local domain.

wtcRemoteTuxDomNWAddr.name: wtcRemoteTuxDomNWAddr
wtcRemoteTuxDomNWAddr.description: Defines the network address of the local domain gateway.

wtcRemoteTuxDomRetryInterval.name: wtcRemoteTuxDomRetryInterval
wtcRemoteTuxDomRetryInterval.description: Defines the number of seconds between automatic attempts to establish a connection to remote domain access points.

wtcRemoteTuxDomTpUsrFile.name: wtcRemoteTuxDomTpUsrFile
wtcRemoteTuxDomTpUsrFile.description: Defines the full path to user password file containing uid/gid information.

wtcRemoteTuxDomFederationName.name: wtcRemoteTuxDomFederationName
wtcRemoteTuxDomFederationName.description: Defines the context at which to federate to a foreign name service.

wtcRemoteTuxDomFederationURL.name: wtcRemoteTuxDomFederationURL
wtcRemoteTuxDomFederationURL.description: Defines the URL for a foreign name service that is federated into JNDI.

wtcRemoteTuxDomLocalAccessPoint.name: wtcRemoteTuxDomLocalAccessPoint
wtcRemoteTuxDomLocalAccessPoint.description: Defines the local domain name from which a remote domain is reached.

wtcRemoteTuxDomDefaultAppKey.name: wtcRemoteTuxDomDefaultAppKey
wtcRemoteTuxDomDefaultAppKey.description: The default AppKey value to be used by the anonymous user and other users who are not defined in the user database if the plug-in allows them to access Tuxedo. Note: The TpUsrFile and LDAP plug-ins do not allow users that are not defined in user database to access Tuxedo unless Allow Anonymous is enabled.

wtcRemoteTuxDomCustomAppKeyClass.name: wtcRemoteTuxDomCustomAppKeyClass
wtcRemoteTuxDomCustomAppKeyClass.description: The full pathname to the custom AppKey generator class. (This class is only relevant if you specify Custom as the AppKey Generator.) Note: This class is loaded at runtime if the Custom AppKey generator plug-in is selected.

wtcRemoteTuxDomTuxedoGidKw.name: wtcRemoteTuxDomTuxedoGidKw
wtcRemoteTuxDomTuxedoGidKw.description: The keyword for Tuxedo GID (Group ID) used in the WlsUser when using the Tuxedo migration utility tpmigldap. (This field is only relevant if you specify LDAP as the AppKey Generator.) Note: The keyword is used to find Tuxedo GID in the user record in the embedded LDAP database.

wtcRemoteTuxDomAllowAnonymous.name: wtcRemoteTuxDomAllowAnonymous
wtcRemoteTuxDomAllowAnonymous.description: Specifies whether the anonymous user is allowed to access remote Tuxedo services. Note: If the anonymous user is allowed to access Tuxedo, the default AppKey will be used for TpUsrFile and LDAP AppKey plug-ins. Interaction with the Custom AppKey plug-in depends on the design of the Custom AppKey generator.

wtcRemoteTuxDomKeepAliveWait.name: wtcRemoteTuxDomKeepAliveWait
wtcRemoteTuxDomKeepAliveWait.description: Return value that tells whether this local Tuxedo access point requires the acknowledgement of Application Level Keep Alive, and how long it will wait without receiving acknowledgement before declare the connection is inaccessable.

wtcRemoteTuxDomCustomAppKeyClassParam.name: wtcRemoteTuxDomCustomAppKeyClassParam
wtcRemoteTuxDomCustomAppKeyClassParam.description: The optional parameters to be used by the custom AppKey class at the class initialization time. (This class is only relevant if you specify Custom as the AppKey Generator.)

wtcRemoteTuxDomTuxedoUidKw.name: wtcRemoteTuxDomTuxedoUidKw
wtcRemoteTuxDomTuxedoUidKw.description: The keyword for Tuxedo UID (User ID) used in the WlsUser when using the Tuxedo migration utility tpmigldap. (This keyword is only relevant if you specify LDAP as the AppKey Generator.) Note: The keyword is used to find Tuxedo UID in the user record in the embedded LDAP database.

wtcRemoteTuxDomKeepAlive.name: wtcRemoteTuxDomKeepAlive
wtcRemoteTuxDomKeepAlive.description: Return value tells whether this local Tuxedo access point is configured with Application Level Keep Alive, and it maximum idle time value before wait timer start ticking.

wtcRemoteTuxDomAppKey.name: wtcRemoteTuxDomAppKey
wtcRemoteTuxDomAppKey.description: Specifies the type of AppKey plug-in used. The allowed values are: TpUsrFile - TpUsrFile is the default plug-in. It uses an imported Tuxedo TPUSR file to provide user security information. Previous releases of WebLogic Tuxedo Connector support this option. LDAP - The LDAP plug-in utilizes an embedded LDAP server to provide user security information. The user record must define the Tuxedo UID and GID information in the description field. This functionality is not supported in previous releases of WebLogic Tuxedo Connector. Custom - The Custom plug-in provides the ability to write your own AppKey generator class to provide the security information required by Tuxedo. This functionality is not supported in previous releases of WebLogic Tuxedo Connector.

wtctBridgeRedirectTable.name: wtctBridgeRedirectTable
wtctBridgeRedirectTable.description: This table represents a wtctBridgeRedirect in the domain.

wtctBridgeRedirectIndex.name: wtctBridgeRedirectIndex
wtctBridgeRedirectIndex.description: Unique value directed from ObjectName which is used as table index

wtctBridgeRedirectParent.name: wtctBridgeRedirectParent
wtctBridgeRedirectParent.description: BEA-proprietary Parent object's identification, with syntax <type>:<name>

wtctBridgeRedirectDirection.name: wtctBridgeRedirectDirection
wtctBridgeRedirectDirection.description: Defines the direction of data flow. Each defined direction is handled by starting a new thread. At least one redirection must be specified in the tBridge configuration or the tBridge will fail to start and an error will be logged.

wtctBridgeRedirectMetaDataFile.name: wtctBridgeRedirectMetaDataFile
wtctBridgeRedirectMetaDataFile.description: Defines the name of the metadataFile URL used to passed to the call WLXT.

wtctBridgeRedirectReplyQ.name: wtctBridgeRedirectReplyQ
wtctBridgeRedirectReplyQ.description: Defines the name of the JMS queue used specifically for synchronous calls to a TUXEDO service. The response is returned to the JMS ReplyQ.

wtctBridgeRedirectSourceAccessPoint.name: wtctBridgeRedirectSourceAccessPoint
wtctBridgeRedirectSourceAccessPoint.description: Defines the name of the local or remote access point where the source is located.

wtctBridgeRedirectSourceName.name: wtctBridgeRedirectSourceName
wtctBridgeRedirectSourceName.description: Defines the name of a source queue or service. Specify a JMS queue name, a TUXEDO queue name, or the name of a TUXEDO service.

wtctBridgeRedirectSourceQspace.name: wtctBridgeRedirectSourceQspace
wtctBridgeRedirectSourceQspace.description: Defines the name of the Qspace for a source location.

wtctBridgeRedirectTargetAccessPoint.name: wtctBridgeRedirectTargetAccessPoint
wtctBridgeRedirectTargetAccessPoint.description: Defines the name of the local or remote access point where the target is located.

wtctBridgeRedirectTargetName.name: wtctBridgeRedirectTargetName

capacityTable.name: capacityTable
capacityTable.description: CapacityMBean defines the maximum number of requests that can be enqueued by all the work managers that share it. The server starts rejecting requests once the capacity threshold is reached. Note that the capacity includes all requests, queued or executing, from the constrained work set. This constraint is independent of the global queue threshold specified by {@link OverloadProtectionMBean#getSharedCapacityForWorkManagers()}. Requests are rejected by performing overload actions. RMI work is rejected by sending back a recoverable exception to the clients. Servlet requests are rejected by sending back a 503 response. domainLibrarySecurityDDModel.name: domainLibrarySecurityDDModel
domainLibrarySecurityDDModel.description: The security model that is used to secure a deployed module. To set this value, you can use the weblogic.Deployer command-line tool, the Deployment Assistant in the Administration Console, the WebLogic Scripting Tool (WLST), or some other JMX client. If you deploy a module using one of the previously mentioned tools and you do not specify a security model value, the module is secured with the security realm's default model ( see {@link weblogic.security.RealmMBean#getSecurityDDModel RealmMBean SecurityDDModel}). If you deploy a module by modifying the domain's config.xml file and restarting the server, and if you do not specify a security model value for the module in config.xml, the module is secured with the DDOnly model, which is the default value of this AppDeploymentMBean attribute. In summary, the order of precedence for the value of this attribute is as follows: If you deploy a module using a runtime deployment utility, the order of precedence is: The value set by the deployment utility. The value set as the security realm's default security model. If you deploy a module by modifying config.xml and restarting the server, the order of precedence is: The value that you specify for the module in config.xml. The default value of this AppDeploymentMBean SecurityDDModel attribute.

fairShareRequestClassTable.name: fairShareRequestClassTable
fairShareRequestClassTable.description: This mbean defines the fair share value to use for this request class. One of the components of work managers is a request class that indicates the proportional of the total server thread use time this request class gets. The default fair share value is 50. Fair shares are reflected in scheduling logic such that as long as multiple fair shares compete, the average number of threads used by each is in proportion to their fair share. For example, consider we only have two fair shares, A and B, having a fair share of 80 and 20, respectively. During a period in which both fair shares are sufficiently requested, say, zero think time and more clients than threads, the probability that a thread will work on behalf of A or B will tend toward 80% or 20%, respectively. The scheduling logic ensures this even when A tends to use a thread for much longer than B. Fair share values can range from 1 to 1000. The default fair share value is 50. jmsMessageLogFileNumberOfFilesLimited.name: jmsMessageLogFileNumberOfFilesLimited
jmsMessageLogFileNumberOfFilesLimited.description: Indicates whether to limit the number of log files that this server instance creates to store old messages. (Requires that you specify a file rotation type of SIZE or TIME.) After the server reaches this limit, it deletes the oldest log file and creates a new log file with the latest suffix. If you do not enable this option, the server creates new files indefinitely and you must clean up these files as you require.

jmsMessageLogFileFileTimeSpan.name: jmsMessageLogFileFileTimeSpan
jmsMessageLogFileFileTimeSpan.description: The interval (in hours) at which the server saves old log messages to another file. (Requires that you specify a file rotation type of TIME.)

jmsMessageLogFileRotationType.name: jmsMessageLogFileRotationType
jmsMessageLogFileRotationType.description: Criteria for moving old log messages to a separate file. NONE Messages accumulate in a single file. You must erase the contents of the file when the size is too large. Note that WebLogic Server sets a threshold size limit of 500 MB before it forces a hard rotation to prevent excessive log file growth. SIZE When the log file reaches the size that you specify in FileMinSize, the server renames the file as FileName.n. TIME At each time interval that you specify in TimeSpan, the server renames the file as FileName.n. After the server renames a file, subsequent messages accumulate in a new file with the name that you specified in FileName.

jmsMessageLogFileFileCount.name: jmsMessageLogFileFileCount
jmsMessageLogFileFileCount.description: The maximum number of log files that the server creates when it rotates the log. This number does not include the file that the server uses to store current messages. (Requires that you enable Number of Files Limited.)

jmsMessageLogFileFileName.name: jmsMessageLogFileFileName
jmsMessageLogFileFileName.description: The name of the file that stores current JMS server log messages. Usually it is a computed value based on the name of the parent of this MBean. For example, for a JMS server log, it is jmsserverName.log. However, if the name of the parent cannot be obtained, the file name is weblogic.log. If you specify a relative pathname, it is interpreted as relative to the server's root directory. To include a time and date stamp in the file name when the log file is rotated, add java.text.SimpleDateFormat variables to the file name. Surround each variable with percentage (%) characters. For example, if the file name is defined to be myjmsserver_%yyyy%_%MM%_%dd%_%hh%_%mm%.log, the log file will be named myserver_yyyy_mm_dd_hh_mm.log. When the log file is rotated, the rotated file name contains the date stamp. For example, if the log file is rotated on 2 April, 2005 at 10:05 AM, the log file that contains the old messages will be named myserver_2005_04_02_10_05.log. If you do not include a time and date stamp, the rotated log files are numbered in order of creation. For example, myjmsserver.log00007.

jmsMessageLogFileFileMinSize.name: jmsMessageLogFileFileMinSize
jmsMessageLogFileFileMinSize.description: The size (1 - 65535 kilobytes) that triggers the server to move log messages to a separate file. After the log file reaches the specified minimum size, the next time the server checks the file size, it will rename the current log file as FileName.n and create a new one to store subsequent messages. (Requires that you specify a file rotation type of Size.)

jmsMessageLogFileBufferSizeKB.name: jmsMessageLogFileBufferSizeKB
jmsMessageLogFileBufferSizeKB.description: Gets the underlying log buffer size in kilo bytes

jmsMessageLogFileDateFormatPattern.name: jmsMessageLogFileDateFormatPattern
jmsMessageLogFileDateFormatPattern.description: The date format pattern used for rendering dates in the log. The DateFormatPattern string conforms to the specification of the java.text.SimpleDateFormat class.

jmsMessageLogFileRotationTime.name: jmsMessageLogFileRotationTime
jmsMessageLogFileRotationTime.description: Determines the start time (hour and minute) for a time-based rotation sequence. At the time that this value specifies, the server renames the current log file. Thereafter, the server renames the log file at an interval that you specify in File Time Span. If the specified time has already past, then the server starts its file rotation immediately. Use the following format: k:mm, where k is the hour in a 24-hour format. mm is the minute

jmsMessageLogFileRotateLogOnStartup.name: jmsMessageLogFileRotateLogOnStartup

jmsMessageLogFileLogFileRotationDir.name: jmsMessageLogFileLogFileRotationDir
jmsMessageLogFileLogFileRotationDir.description: The directory where the rotated log files will be stored. By default the rotated files are stored in the same directory where the log file is stored.
