wlssnmpProxyType.description: Returns the type of the MBean.

wlssnmpProxyTimeout.name: wlssnmpProxyTimeout
wlssnmpProxyTimeout.description: The number of milliseconds that the WebLogic Server SNMP agent waits for a response to requests that it forwards to this proxy agent. If the interval elapses without a response, the WebLogic SNMP agent sends an error to the requesting manager.

wlssnmpProxySecurityName.name: wlssnmpProxySecurityName
wlssnmpProxySecurityName.description: The user name on whose behalf the WebLogic SNMP agent forwards v3 requests. If not specified, the request is forwarded as a v1 request. If you specify a security name, you must also specify a security level that is equal to or lower than the security level that is configured for communication between the WebLogic SNMP agent and SNMP managers. For example, if the WebLogic SNMP agent requires incoming SNMPv3 requests to use the authentication protocol but no privacy protocol, the security level for this proxy must be either Authentication Only or None. Note that if you want to use the authorization or privacy protocols, you must configure credential mapping in the WebLogic Server security realm. The WebLogic SNMP agent cannot forward or pass through the credentials that are contained in SNMPv3 requests from SNMP managers. Instead, the agent authenticates and performs other security operations on incoming requests, and then constructs a new request to forward to a proxied agent.

wlssnmpProxyPort.name: wlssnmpProxyPort
wlssnmpProxyPort.description: The port number on which this proxied SNMP agent is listening.

wlssnmpProxySecurityLevel.name: wlssnmpProxySecurityLevel
wlssnmpProxySecurityLevel.description: The security level that the proxied SNMP agent expects for the specified security name.

wlssnmpProxyOidRoot.name: wlssnmpProxyOidRoot
wlssnmpProxyOidRoot.description: The root of the object identifier (OID) tree that this proxied SNMP agent controls.

wlssnmpProxyCommunity.name: wlssnmpProxyCommunity
wlssnmpProxyCommunity.description: The community name to be passed on for all SNMPv1 requests to this proxied SNMP agent. If you specify a security name for this proxied agent, the WebLogic SNMP agent ignores this community name. Instead, the agent encodes the security name in an SNMPv3 request and forwards the SNMPv3 request to this proxied agent.

wlssnmpProxyName.name: wlssnmpProxyName
wlssnmpProxyName.description: The user-specified name of this MBean instance. This name is included as one of the key properties in the MBean's javax.management.ObjectName: Name=user-specified-name

wlssnmpTrapDestinationTable.description: This MBean describes a destination to which an SNMP agent sends SNMP TRAP and INFORM notifications. wlssnmpTrapDestinationType.name: wlssnmpTrapDestinationType
wlssnmpTrapDestinationType.description: Returns the type of the MBean.

wlssnmpTrapDestinationHost.name: wlssnmpTrapDestinationHost
wlssnmpTrapDestinationHost.description: The DNS name or IP address of the computer on which the SNMP manager is running. The WebLogic SNMP agent sends trap notifications to the host and port that you specify.

wlssnmpTrapDestinationSecurityName.name: wlssnmpTrapDestinationSecurityName
wlssnmpTrapDestinationSecurityName.description: Specifies the user name that the WebLogic Server SNMP agent encodes into SNMPv3 responses or notifications. Requires you to create a credential map for this user name in the WebLogic Server security realm. The credential map contains an authentication password and an optional privacy password for this user. The user name and passwords must match the credentials required by the SNMP manager that this trap destination represents.

wlssnmpTrapDestinationCommunity.description: The password (community name) that a WebLogic Server SNMP agent sends to the SNMP manager when the agent generates SNMPv1 or SNMPv2 notifications. The community name that you enter in this trap destination must match the name that the SNMP manager defines.

securityConfigurationWebAppFilesCaseInse.name: securityConfigurationWebAppFilesCaseInsensitive
securityConfigurationWebAppFilesCaseInse.description: This property defines the case sensitive URL-pattern matching behavior for security constraints, servlets, filters, virtual-hosts, etc. in the WebApp container and external security policies. When the value is set to 'os', the pattern matching will be case- sensitive on all platforms except the Windows file system. Note that on non-Windows file systems, WebLogic doesn't enforce case sensitivity and relies on the file system for optimization. Therefore, if you have a Windows Samba mount from UNIX or Mac OS that has been installed in case-insensitive mode, there is a chance of security risk. In that case, please specify case-insensitive lookups by setting this attribute to true. Note that this property is used to preserve backward compatibility on Windows file systems. In prior releases, WebLogic was case- insensitive on Windows. Starting with 9.0 release the URL-pattern matching will be strictly enforced. During the upgrade of older domains the value of this parameter is explicitly set to 'os' by the upgrade plug-in, in order to preserve backward compatibility.

securityConfigurationCrossDomainSecurity.name: securityConfigurationCrossDomainSecurityEnabled
securityConfigurationCrossDomainSecurity.description: Indicates whether or not cross-domain security is enabled

securityConfigurationEnforceStrictURLPat.name: securityConfigurationEnforceStrictURLPattern
securityConfigurationEnforceStrictURLPat.description: Whether or not the system should enforce strict URL pattern or not.

securityConfigurationConnectionFilter.name: securityConfigurationConnectionFilter
securityConfigurationConnectionFilter.description: The name of the Java class that implements a connection filter (that is, the weblogic.security.net.ConnectionFilter interface). If no class name is specified, no connection filter will be used. This attribute replaces the deprecated ConnectionFilter attribute on the SecurityMBean.

securityConfigurationConsoleFullDelegati.name: securityConfigurationConsoleFullDelegationEnabled
securityConfigurationConsoleFullDelegati.description: Indicates whether the console is enabled for fully delegate authorization.

securityConfigurationDowngradeUntrustedP.name: securityConfigurationDowngradeUntrustedPrincipals
securityConfigurationDowngradeUntrustedP.description: Whether or not to downgrade to anonymous principals that cannot be verified. This is useful for server-server communication between untrusted domains.

securityConfigurationName.name: securityConfigurationName

securityConfigurationConnectionLoggerEna.name: securityConfigurationConnectionLoggerEnabled
securityConfigurationConnectionLoggerEna.description: Specifies whether this WebLogic Server domain should log accepted connections. This attribute can be used by a system administrator to dynamically check the incoming connections in the log file to determine if filtering needs to be performed. This attribute replaces the deprecated ConnectionLoggerEnabled attribute on the SecurityMBean.

securityConfigurationEnforceValidBasicAu.name: securityConfigurationEnforceValidBasicAuthCredentials
securityConfigurationEnforceValidBasicAu.description: Whether or not the system should allow requests with invalid Basic Authentication credentials to access unsecure resources.

securityConfigurationNodeManagerUsername.name: securityConfigurationNodeManagerUsername

serverFailureTriggerTable.name: serverFailureTriggerTable
serverFailureTriggerTable.description: Configuration to mark the server as failed when threads are stuck. A failed server in turn can be configured to shutdown or go into admin state.

serverFailureTriggerType.name: serverFailureTriggerType
serverFailureTriggerType.description: Returns the type of the MBean.

serverFailureTriggerMaxStuckThreadTime.name: serverFailureTriggerMaxStuckThreadTime
serverFailureTriggerMaxStuckThreadTime.description: The number of seconds that a thread must be continually working before this server diagnoses the thread as being stuck. For example, if you set this to 600 seconds, WebLogic Server considers a thread to be 'stuck' after 600 seconds of continuous use.

serverFailureTriggerStuckThreadCount.name: serverFailureTriggerStuckThreadCount
serverFailureTriggerStuckThreadCount.description: The number of stuck threads after which the server is transitioned into FAILED state. There are options in OverloadProtectionMBean to suspend and shutdown a FAILED server. By default, the server continues to run in FAILED state. If the StuckThreadCount value is set to zero then the server never transitions into FAILED server irrespective of the number of stuck threads.

serverFailureTriggerName.name: serverFailureTriggerName
serverFailureTriggerName.description: The user-specified name of this MBean instance. This name is included as one of the key properties in the MBean's javax.management.ObjectName: Name=user-specified-name

shutdownClassTable.name: shutdownClassTable
shutdownClassTable.description: Provides methods for configuring a shutdown class. A shutdown class is a Java program that is automatically loaded and executed when a WebLogic Server instance is shut down gracefully. Deprecation of MBeanHome and Type-Safe Interfaces This is a type-safe interface for a WebLogic Server MBean, which you can import into your client classes and access through weblogic.management.MBeanHome. As of 9.0, the MBeanHome interface and all type-safe interfaces for WebLogic Server MBeans are deprecated. Instead, client classes that interact with WebLogic Server MBeans should use standard JMX design patterns in which clients use the javax.management.MBeanServerConnection interface to discover MBeans, attributes, and attribute types at runtime. For more information, see 'Developing Manageable Applications with JMX' on http://edocs.bea.com.

shutdownClassType.name: shutdownClassType
shutdownClassType.description: Returns the type of the MBean.

shutdownClassDeploymentOrder.name: shutdownClassDeploymentOrder
shutdownClassDeploymentOrder.description: A priority that the server uses to determine when it deploys an item. The priority is relative to other deployable items of the same type. For example, the server prioritizes and deploys all EJBs before it prioritizes and deploys startup classes. Items with the lowest Deployment Order value are deployed first. There is no guarantee on the order of deployments with equal Deployment Order values. There is no guarantee of ordering across clusters.

shutdownClassArguments.name: shutdownClassArguments
shutdownClassArguments.description: Arguments that a server uses to initialize a class. Separate multiple arguments with a comma. For example: first=MyFirstName,last=MyLastName

shutdownClassName.name: shutdownClassName
shutdownClassName.description: The user-specified name of this MBean instance. This name is included as one of the key properties in the MBean's javax.management.ObjectName: Name=user-specified-name

shutdownClassClassName.name: shutdownClassClassName
shutdownClassClassName.description: The fully qualified name of a class to load and run. The class must be on the server's classpath. For example, mycompany.mypackage.myclass

singleSignOnServicesTable.name: singleSignOnServicesTable
singleSignOnServicesTable.description: This MBean represents configuration for SAML 2.0-based local site Single Sign-On Services. Deprecation of MBeanHome and Type-Safe Interfaces This is a type-safe interface for a WebLogic Server MBean, which you can import into your client classes and access through weblogic.management.MBeanHome. As of 9.0, the MBeanHome interface and all type-safe interfaces for WebLogic Server MBeans are deprecated. Instead, client classes that interact with WebLogic Server MBeans should use standard JMX design patterns in which clients use the javax.management.MBeanServerConnection interface to discover MBeans, attributes, and attribute types at runtime. For more information, see 'Developing Manageable Applications with JMX' on http://edocs.bea.com.

singleSignOnServicesArtifactMaxCacheSize.name: singleSignOnServicesArtifactMaxCacheSize
singleSignOnServicesArtifactMaxCacheSize.description: Gets the maximum size of the artifact cache. This cache is of artifacts issued by the local site that are awaiting referencing by a partner. Specify '0' to indicate that the cache is unbounded.

singleSignOnServicesIdentityProviderRedi.name: singleSignOnServicesIdentityProviderRedirectBindingEnabled
singleSignOnServicesIdentityProviderRedi.description: Gets the identity provider redirect binding enabled flag

singleSignOnServicesIdentityProviderPref.name: singleSignOnServicesIdentityProviderPreferredBinding
singleSignOnServicesIdentityProviderPref.description: Gets the preferred binding type for endpoints of identity provider services

singleSignOnServicesWantArtifactRequests.name: singleSignOnServicesWantArtifactRequestsSigned
singleSignOnServicesWantArtifactRequests.description: Gets the want <AuthnRequest> docuemnts signed flag

singleSignOnServicesTransportLayerSecuri.name: singleSignOnServicesTransportLayerSecurityKeyAlias
singleSignOnServicesTransportLayerSecuri.description: Get the TLS/SSL key alias. The key is used to establish outgoing TLS/SSL connections.

singleSignOnServicesSSOSigningKeyAlias.name: singleSignOnServicesSSOSigningKeyAlias
singleSignOnServicesSSOSigningKeyAlias.description: Get the SSO Signing key alias. The key is used to generate signatures on all the outgoing documents, like <AuthnRequest>, <Response>

singleSignOnServicesLoginReturnQueryPara.name: singleSignOnServicesLoginReturnQueryParameter
singleSignOnServicesLoginReturnQueryPara.description: Gets the name of the query string parameter to extract from the response following use of Login URL

singleSignOnServicesAuthnRequestTimeout.name: singleSignOnServicesAuthnRequestTimeout
singleSignOnServicesAuthnRequestTimeout.description: Gets the maximum timeout (in seconds) of <AuthnRequest> documents stored in the local cache. This cache is of documents issued by the local SP that are awaiting response from a partner IdP. Documents that reach this maximum timeout age will be expired from the local cache even if no response has yet been received from the partner IdP. If a reponse is subsequently returned by the partner IdP, the cache will behave as if the <AuthnRequest> had never been generated.

singleSignOnServicesPOSTOneUseCheckEnabl.name: singleSignOnServicesPOSTOneUseCheckEnabled
singleSignOnServicesPOSTOneUseCheckEnabl.description: Specifies whether the POST one-use check is enabled.

singleSignOnServicesIdentityProviderArti.name: singleSignOnServicesIdentityProviderArtifactBindingEnabled
singleSignOnServicesIdentityProviderArti.description: Gets the identity provider artifact binding enabled flag

singleSignOnServicesWantTransportLayerSe.name: singleSignOnServicesWantTransportLayerSecurityClientAuthentication
singleSignOnServicesWantTransportLayerSe.description: Gets the want TLS/SSL client authentication flag. If true, callers to TLS/SSL bindings of the local site must specify client authentication (two-way SSL) and the identity specified must validate against TLS certificate of the binding client partner.

singleSignOnServicesIdentityProviderEnab.name: singleSignOnServicesIdentityProviderEnabled
singleSignOnServicesIdentityProviderEnab.description: Gets the identity provider enabled flag

singleSignOnServicesLoginURL.name: singleSignOnServicesLoginURL
singleSignOnServicesLoginURL.description: Gets the Login URL to redirect callers to when IdP receives a request from an anonymous end user.

singleSignOnServicesArtifactTimeout.name: singleSignOnServicesArtifactTimeout
singleSignOnServicesArtifactTimeout.description: Gets the maximum timeout (in seconds) of artifacts stored in the local cache. This cache is of artifacts issued by the local site that are awaiting referencing by a partner. Artifacts that reach this maximum timeout age will be expired from the local cache even if no reference request has yet been received from the partner. If a reference request is subsequently received from the partner, the cache will behave as if the artifact had never been generated.

singleSignOnServicesDefaultURL.name: singleSignOnServicesDefaultURL
singleSignOnServicesDefaultURL.description: Gets the SP's Default URL. When an unsolicited SSO response arrives at the SP without an accompanying target URL, the user (if authenticated) is redirected to the default URL.

singleSignOnServicesWantBasicAuthClientA.name: singleSignOnServicesWantBasicAuthClientAuthentication
singleSignOnServicesWantBasicAuthClientA.description: Gets the want Basic Authentication client authentication flag. If true, callers to HTTPS bindings of the local site must specify a basic authentication header and the username and password must validate against the basic authetnication values of the binding client partner.

singleSignOnServicesType.name: singleSignOnServicesType
singleSignOnServicesType.description: Returns the type of the MBean.

singleSignOnServicesRecipientCheckEnable.name: singleSignOnServicesRecipientCheckEnabled
singleSignOnServicesRecipientCheckEnable.description: Specifies whether the recipient/destination check is enabled. When true, the recipient of the SAML Request/Response must match the URL in the HTTP Request.

singleSignOnServicesErrorPath.name: singleSignOnServicesErrorPath
singleSignOnServicesErrorPath.description: Gets the Error Path URL. Partner sites may redirect users to this URL for more information if SSO fails.

singleSignOnServicesAuthnRequestMaxCache.name: singleSignOnServicesAuthnRequestMaxCacheSize
singleSignOnServicesAuthnRequestMaxCache.description: Gets the maximum size of the <AuthnRequest> document cache. This cache is of documents issued by the local SP that are awaiting response from a partner IdP. Specify '0' to indicate that the cache is unbounded.

singleSignOnServicesReplicatedCacheEnabl.name: singleSignOnServicesReplicatedCacheEnabled
singleSignOnServicesReplicatedCacheEnabl.description: Gets the Use Replicated Cache flag. If true, persistent cache(LDAP or RDBMS) will be used to store SAML2 artifacts and authentication requests. Otherwise, artifacts and requests will be saved in memory.

singleSignOnServicesName.name: singleSignOnServicesName
singleSignOnServicesName.description: The user-specified name of this MBean instance. This name is included as one of the key properties in the MBean's javax.management.ObjectName: Name=user-specified-name

singleSignOnServicesBasicAuthUsername.name: singleSignOnServicesBasicAuthUsername
singleSignOnServicesBasicAuthUsername.description: Get the Basic Authentication username. This username is used to assign Basic Authentication credentials to outgoing HTTPS connections.

singleSignOnServicesServiceProviderPOSTB.name: singleSignOnServicesServiceProviderPOSTBindingEnabled
singleSignOnServicesServiceProviderPOSTB.description: Gets the service provider POST binding enabled flag

singleSignOnServicesServiceProviderArtif.name: singleSignOnServicesServiceProviderArtifactBindingEnabled
singleSignOnServicesServiceProviderArtif.description: Gets the service provider artifact binding enabled flag

singleSignOnServicesWantAssertionsSigned.name: singleSignOnServicesWantAssertionsSigned
singleSignOnServicesWantAssertionsSigned.description: Advertized flag indicating requirement that incoming assertions be signed

singleSignOnServicesWantAuthnRequestsSig.name: singleSignOnServicesWantAuthnRequestsSigned
singleSignOnServicesWantAuthnRequestsSig.description: Gets the want <AuthnRequest> docuemnts signed flag

singleSignOnServicesServiceProviderPrefe.name: singleSignOnServicesServiceProviderPreferredBinding
singleSignOnServicesServiceProviderPrefe.description: Gets the preferred binding type for endpoints of service provider services

singleSignOnServicesIdentityProviderPOST.name: singleSignOnServicesIdentityProviderPOSTBindingEnabled
singleSignOnServicesIdentityProviderPOST.description: Gets the identity provider POST binding enabled flag

singletonServiceAppScopedTable.name: singletonServiceAppScopedTable
singletonServiceAppScopedTable.description: A service that will be automatically maintained as a Singleton in a cluster. There will always be exactly one instance of it active at any given time. Deprecation of MBeanHome and Type-Safe Interfaces This is a type-safe interface for a WebLogic Server MBean, which you can import into your client classes and access through weblogic.management.MBeanHome. As of 9.0, the MBeanHome interface and all type-safe interfaces for WebLogic Server MBeans are deprecated. Instead, client classes that interact with WebLogic Server MBeans should use standard JMX design patterns in which clients use the javax.management.MBeanServerConnection interface to discover MBeans, attributes, and attribute types at runtime. For more information, see 'Developing Manageable Applications with JMX' on http://edocs.bea.com.

singletonServiceAppScopedType.name: singletonServiceAppScopedType
singletonServiceAppScopedType.description: Returns the type of the MBean.

singletonServiceAppScopedCompatibilityNa.name: singletonServiceAppScopedCompatibilityName
singletonServiceAppScopedCompatibilityNa.description: This is only set for beans created as a result of conversion from an 8.1 application configured using ApplicationMBean and ComponentMBean. Standalone modules in 8.1 have both an ApplicationMBean name and ComponentMBean name. This attribute stores the name of the latter, to be used when the server creates the transient ComponentMBean for backward compatibility.

singletonServiceAppScopedMillisToSleepBe.name: singletonServiceAppScopedMillisToSleepBetweenAttempts
singletonServiceAppScopedMillisToSleepBe.description: Controls how long of a pause there should be between the migration attempts described in getAdditionalMigrationAttempts(). Note that this delay only happens when the service has failed to come up on every server. It does not cause any sort of delay between attempts to migrate otherwise.

singletonServiceAppScopedModuleType.name: singletonServiceAppScopedModuleType
singletonServiceAppScopedModuleType.description: The values match those defined by jsr88. This attribute may move to another MBean.

singletonServiceAppScopedName.name: singletonServiceAppScopedName
singletonServiceAppScopedName.description: Unique identifier for this bean instance. It is used by the application container to match the module in the application package to the targeting information in the configuration. For modules within an EAR, the name should be the URI of the module as defined in the META-INF/application.xml deployment descriptor. There is an exception to this for web applications. See below. For web modules in an EAR, the name should always equal the context root of that webapp, because the URI is not always unique

singletonServiceAppScopedAdditionalMigra.name: singletonServiceAppScopedAdditionalMigrationAttempts
singletonServiceAppScopedAdditionalMigra.description: A migratable service could fail to come up on every possible configured server. This attribute controls how many further attempts, after the service has failed on every server at least once, should be tried. Note that each attempt specified here indicates another full circut of migrations amongst all the configured servers. So for a 3-server cluster, and a value of 2, a total of 4 additional migrations will be attempted. (the original server is never a valid destination)

singletonServiceAppScopedClassName.name: singletonServiceAppScopedClassName
singletonServiceAppScopedClassName.description: The fully qualified name of a class to load and run. The class must be on the server's classpath. For example, mycompany.mypackage.myclass

singletonServiceTable.name: singletonServiceTable
singletonServiceTable.description: A service that will be automatically maintained as a Singleton in a cluster. There will always be exactly one instance of it active at any given time. Deprecation of MBeanHome and Type-Safe Interfaces This is a type-safe interface for a WebLogic Server MBean, which you can import into your client classes and access through weblogic.management.MBeanHome. As of 9.0, the MBeanHome interface and all type-safe interfaces for WebLogic Server MBeans are deprecated. Instead, client classes that interact with WebLogic Server MBeans should use standard JMX design patterns in which clients use the javax.management.MBeanServerConnection interface to discover MBeans, attributes, and attribute types at runtime. For more information, see 'Developing Manageable Applications with JMX' on http://edocs.bea.com.

singletonServiceType.name: singletonServiceType
singletonServiceType.description: Returns the type of the MBean.

singletonServiceMillisToSleepBetweenAtte.name: singletonServiceMillisToSleepBetweenAttempts
singletonServiceMillisToSleepBetweenAtte.description: Controls how long of a pause there should be between the migration attempts described in getAdditionalMigrationAttempts(). Note that this delay only happens when the service has failed to come up on every server. It does not cause any sort of delay between attempts to migrate otherwise.

singletonServiceName.name: singletonServiceName
singletonServiceName.description: The user-specified name of this MBean instance. This name is included as one of the key properties in the MBean's javax.management.ObjectName: Name=user-specified-name

singletonServiceAdditionalMigrationAttem.name: singletonServiceAdditionalMigrationAttempts
singletonServiceAdditionalMigrationAttem.description: A migratable service could fail to come up on every possible configured server. This attribute controls how many further attempts, after the service has failed on every server at least once, should be tried. Note that each attempt specified here indicates another full circut of migrations amongst all the configured servers. So for a 3-server cluster, and a value of 2, a total of 4 additional migrations will be attempted. (the original server is never a valid destination)

singletonServiceClassName.name: singletonServiceClassName
singletonServiceClassName.description: The fully qualified name of a class to load and run. The class must be on the server's classpath. For example, mycompany.mypackage.myclass

stuckThreadActionTable.name: stuckThreadActionTable
stuckThreadActionTable.description: Configuration that deals with handling of stuck threads. Configured actions are executed when the max stuck thread limit is reached. Actions include shutting down the work manager, putting the app in admin mode or marking the server as failed. This MBean is not directly exposed to JMX clients. It is only used by the console. Deprecation of MBeanHome and Type-Safe Interfaces This is a type-safe interface for a WebLogic Server MBean, which you can import into your client classes and access through weblogic.management.MBeanHome. As of 9.0, the MBeanHome interface and all type-safe interfaces for WebLogic Server MBeans are deprecated. Instead, client classes that interact with WebLogic Server MBeans should use standard JMX design patterns in which clients use the javax.management.MBeanServerConnection interface to discover MBeans, attributes, and attribute types at runtime. For more information, see 'Developing Manageable Applications with JMX' on http://edocs.bea.com.

stuckThreadActionType.name: stuckThreadActionType
stuckThreadActionType.description: Returns the type of the MBean.

stuckThreadActionName.name: stuckThreadActionName
stuckThreadActionName.description: The user-specified name of this MBean instance. This name is included as one of the key properties in the MBean's javax.management.ObjectName: Name=user-specified-name

unixMachineTable.name: unixMachineTable
unixMachineTable.description: This bean represents a machine that is running the UNIX operating system. It extends MachineMBean with properties specific to the UNIX platform.

unixMachineType.name: unixMachineType
unixMachineType.description: Returns the type of the MBean.

unixMachinePostBindUID.name: unixMachinePostBindUID
unixMachinePostBindUID.description: The UNIX user ID (UID) that a server running on this machine will run under after it has carried out all privileged startup actions. Otherwise, the server will continue to run under the account under which it was started.(Requires that you enable Post-Bind UID.)

unixMachinePostBindUIDEnabled.name: unixMachinePostBindUIDEnabled
unixMachinePostBindUIDEnabled.description: Specifies whether a server running on this machine binds to a UNIX User ID (UID) after it has carried out all privileged startup actions.

unixMachinePostBindGID.name: unixMachinePostBindGID
unixMachinePostBindGID.description: The UNIX group ID (GID) that a server running on this machine will run under after it has carried out all privileged startup actions. Otherwise, the server will continue to run under the group under which it was started.(Requires that you enable Post-Bind GID.)

unixMachinePostBindGIDEnabled.name: unixMachinePostBindGIDEnabled
unixMachinePostBindGIDEnabled.description: Specifies whether a server running on this machine binds to a UNIX Group ID (GID) after it has carried out all privileged startup actions.

unixMachineName.name: unixMachineName
unixMachineName.description: The user-specified name of this MBean instance. This name is included as one of the key properties in the MBean's javax.management.ObjectName: Name=user-specified-name

virtualDestinationTable.name: virtualDestinationTable
virtualDestinationTable.description: This class represents a virtual destination. In 7.0 JMS has distributed destination, which is a form of the virtual destination. Deprecation of MBeanHome and Type-Safe Interfaces This is a type-safe interface for a WebLogic Server MBean, which you can import into your client classes and access through weblogic.management.MBeanHome. As of 9.0, the MBeanHome interface and all type-safe interfaces for WebLogic Server MBeans are deprecated. Instead, client classes that interact with WebLogic Server MBeans should use standard JMX design patterns in which clients use the javax.management.MBeanServerConnection interface to discover MBeans, attributes, and attribute types at runtime. For more information, see 'Developing Manageable Applications with JMX' on http://edocs.bea.com.

virtualDestinationType.name: virtualDestinationType
virtualDestinationType.description: Returns the type of the MBean.

virtualDestinationDeploymentOrder.name: virtualDestinationDeploymentOrder
virtualDestinationDeploymentOrder.description: A priority that the server uses to determine when it deploys an item. The priority is relative to other deployable items of the same type. For example, the server prioritizes and deploys all EJBs before it prioritizes and deploys startup classes. Items with the lowest Deployment Order value are deployed first. There is no guarantee on the order of deployments with equal Deployment Order values. There is no guarantee of ordering across clusters.

virtualDestinationJNDIName.name: virtualDestinationJNDIName
virtualDestinationJNDIName.description: The JNDI name used to look up a virtual destination within the JNDI namespace. Applications can use the JNDI name to look up the virtual destination. If not specified, then the destination is not bound into the JNDI namespace.

virtualDestinationName.name: virtualDestinationName
virtualDestinationName.description: The user-specified name of this MBean instance. This name is included as one of the key properties in the MBean's javax.management.ObjectName: Name=user-specified-name

wldfDataRetirementByAgeTable.name: wldfDataRetirementByAgeTable
wldfDataRetirementByAgeTable.description: This MBean specifies how data retirement for a WLDF archive will be performed based on the age of records in WLDF archives.

wldfDataRetirementByAgeType.name: wldfDataRetirementByAgeType
wldfDataRetirementByAgeType.description: Returns the type of the MBean.

wldfDataRetirementByAgeRetirementTime.name: wldfDataRetirementByAgeRetirementTime
wldfDataRetirementByAgeRetirementTime.description: This attribute specifies the hour of day at which the the data retirement task will first run during the day.

wldfDataRetirementByAgeRetirementPeriod.name: wldfDataRetirementByAgeRetirementPeriod
wldfDataRetirementByAgeRetirementPeriod.description: This attribute specifies the period in hours at which the data retirement task will be periodically performed for the archive during the day after it is first executed. The value of this attribute must be positive

wldfDataRetirementByAgeRetirementAge.name: wldfDataRetirementByAgeRetirementAge
wldfDataRetirementByAgeRetirementAge.description: Retirement age for records in hours. Older records will be eligible for deletion.

wldfDataRetirementByAgeArchiveName.name: wldfDataRetirementByAgeArchiveName
wldfDataRetirementByAgeArchiveName.description: Name of the archive for which data retirement is configured

wldfDataRetirementByAgeName.name: wldfDataRetirementByAgeName
wldfDataRetirementByAgeName.description: The user-specified name of this MBean instance. This name is included as one of the key properties in the MBean's javax.management.ObjectName: Name=user-specified-name

wldfServerDiagnosticTable.name: wldfServerDiagnosticTable
wldfServerDiagnosticTable.description: Use this interface to configure the WebLogic Diagnostic Framework (WLDF) components that are defined for each WebLogic Server instance.

wldfServerDiagnosticType.name: wldfServerDiagnosticType
wldfServerDiagnosticType.description: Returns the type of the MBean.

wldfServerDiagnosticSynchronousEventPers.name: wldfServerDiagnosticSynchronousEventPersistenceEnabled
wldfServerDiagnosticSynchronousEventPers.description: Specifies the instrumentation events persistence policy. If true, events will be persisted synchronously within the same thread. If false, events will be queued up to be persisted in a separate thread.

wldfServerDiagnosticEventPersistenceInte.name: wldfServerDiagnosticEventPersistenceInterval
wldfServerDiagnosticEventPersistenceInte.description: The interval, in milliseconds, at which queued up instrumentation events will be periodically dispatched to the archive.

wldfServerDiagnosticPreferredStoreSizeLi.name: wldfServerDiagnosticPreferredStoreSizeLimit
wldfServerDiagnosticPreferredStoreSizeLi.description: Return the preferred limit on the size of diagnostic store file in MB.

wldfServerDiagnosticImageTimeout.name: wldfServerDiagnosticImageTimeout
wldfServerDiagnosticImageTimeout.description: The default timeout period, in minutes, that the server uses to delay future diagnostic image-capture requests.

wldfServerDiagnosticDiagnosticStoreDir.name: wldfServerDiagnosticDiagnosticStoreDir
wldfServerDiagnosticDiagnosticStoreDir.description: The directory in which the current server maintains its diagnostic store.

wldfServerDiagnosticDiagnosticDataArchiv.name: wldfServerDiagnosticDiagnosticDataArchiveType
wldfServerDiagnosticDiagnosticDataArchiv.description: Determines whether the current server persists its harvested metrics and event data in a diagnostic store (file-based store) or a JDBC based archive. The default store is file-based.

wldfServerDiagnosticDiagnosticContextEna.name: wldfServerDiagnosticDiagnosticContextEnabled
wldfServerDiagnosticDiagnosticContextEna.description: If true, diagnostic context creation is enabled. If false, the diagnostic context will not be created when requested. However, if the diagnostics context already exists because it was propagated from another VM or was created through the DyeInjection monitor, the context will be made available.

wldfServerDiagnosticStoreSizeCheckPeriod.name: wldfServerDiagnosticStoreSizeCheckPeriod
wldfServerDiagnosticStoreSizeCheckPeriod.description: Return the period in hours at which diagnostic store file size check will be performed

wldfServerDiagnosticEventsImageCaptureIn.name: wldfServerDiagnosticEventsImageCaptureInterval
wldfServerDiagnosticEventsImageCaptureIn.description: The time span, in milliseconds, for which recently archived events will be captured in the diagnostic image. All events archived on or after ( System.currentTimeMillis() - interval ) will be captured.

wldfServerDiagnosticImageDir.name: wldfServerDiagnosticImageDir
wldfServerDiagnosticImageDir.description: The default directory where the server stores captured diagnostic images. If you specify a relative pathname, the root of that path is the server's root directory. If the directory does not exist, it will be created when the WebLogic Diagnostic Framework is initialized on the server. Note that each image capture request can override this default directory location.

wldfServerDiagnosticDataRetirementEnable.name: wldfServerDiagnosticDataRetirementEnabled
wldfServerDiagnosticDataRetirementEnable.description: This attribute controls if configuration based data retirement functionality is enabled on the server. If disabled, all retirement policies will be disabled.

wldfServerDiagnosticName.name: wldfServerDiagnosticName
wldfServerDiagnosticName.description: The user-specified name of this MBean instance. This name is included as one of the key properties in the MBean's javax.management.ObjectName: Name=user-specified-name

wldfSystemResourceTable.name: wldfSystemResourceTable
wldfSystemResourceTable.description: This bean defines a system-level WebLogic Diagnostic Framework (WLDF) resource. It links a separate descriptor that specifies the definition.

wldfSystemResourceType.name: wldfSystemResourceType
wldfSystemResourceType.description: Returns the type of the MBean.

wldfSystemResourceCompatibilityName.name: wldfSystemResourceCompatibilityName
wldfSystemResourceCompatibilityName.description: This is only set for beans created as a result of conversion from an 8.1 application configured using ApplicationMBean and ComponentMBean. Standalone modules in 8.1 have both an ApplicationMBean name and ComponentMBean name. This attribute stores the name of the latter, to be used when the server creates the transient ComponentMBean for backward compatibility.

wldfSystemResourceDeploymentOrder.name: wldfSystemResourceDeploymentOrder
wldfSystemResourceDeploymentOrder.description: A numerical value that indicates when this unit is deployed, relative to other DeployableUnits on a server, during startup. Units with lower Load Order values are deployed before those with higher values.

wldfSystemResourceDeploymentPrincipalNam.name: wldfSystemResourceDeploymentPrincipalName
wldfSystemResourceDeploymentPrincipalNam.description: A string value that indicates what principal should be used when deploying the file or archive during startup and shutdown. This principal will be used to set the current subject when calling out into application code for interfaces such as ApplicationLifecycleListener, If no principal name is specifed, then the anonymous principal will be used.

wldfSystemResourceDescriptorFileName.name: wldfSystemResourceDescriptorFileName
wldfSystemResourceDescriptorFileName.description: The name of the descriptor file that contains the XML configuration information for this system-level resource. The location of this file is a relative path rooted at DOMAIN_DIR/config. By default the file resides in the DOMAIN_DIR/config/diagnostics directory, and derives its name from the bean name using the following pattern: .xml Note that the filename is a read-only property, which is set when the WLDF resource is created.

wldfSystemResourceDescription.name: wldfSystemResourceDescription
wldfSystemResourceDescription.description: Optional short description of this WLDFSystemResource. If provided, the WebLogic Server Administration Console will display the resource description.

wldfSystemResourceModuleType.name: wldfSystemResourceModuleType
wldfSystemResourceModuleType.description: The values match those defined by jsr88. This attribute may move to another MBean.

wldfSystemResourceName.name: wldfSystemResourceName
wldfSystemResourceName.description: Unique identifier for this bean instance.

wtcServerTable.name: wtcServerTable
wtcServerTable.description: This MBean defines a WTC Server. Deprecation of MBeanHome and Type-Safe Interfaces This is a type-safe interface for a WebLogic Server MBean, which you can import into your client classes and access through weblogic.management.MBeanHome. As of 9.0, the MBeanHome interface and all type-safe interfaces for WebLogic Server MBeans are deprecated. Instead, client classes that interact with WebLogic Server MBeans should use standard JMX design patterns in which clients use the javax.management.MBeanServerConnection interface to discover MBeans, attributes, and attribute types at runtime. For more information, see 'Developing Manageable Applications with JMX' on http://edocs.bea.com.

wtcServerType.name: wtcServerType
wtcServerType.description: Returns the type of the MBean.

wtcServerName.name: wtcServerName
wtcServerName.description: The user-specified name of this MBean instance. This name is included as one of the key properties in the MBean's javax.management.ObjectName: Name=user-specified-name

wtcServerDeploymentOrder.name: wtcServerDeploymentOrder
wtcServerDeploymentOrder.description: A priority that the server uses to determine when it deploys an item. The priority is relative to other deployable items of the same type. For example, the server prioritizes and deploys all EJBs before it prioritizes and deploys startup classes. Items with the lowest Deployment Order value are deployed first. There is no guarantee on the order of deployments with equal Deployment Order values. There is no guarantee of ordering across clusters.

webAppContainerTable.name: webAppContainerTable
webAppContainerTable.description: This MBean is used to specify domain-wide defaults for the WebApp container. In general, these properties can be overridden at the cluster level (in ClusterMBean, if the same property is present there), the server level (in ServerMBean, if the same property is present there) or for a specific Web application (in weblogic.xml). Deprecation of MBeanHome and Type-Safe Interfaces This is a type-safe interface for a WebLogic Server MBean, which you can import into your client classes and access through weblogic.management.MBeanHome. As of 9.0, the MBeanHome interface and all type-safe interfaces for WebLogic Server MBeans are deprecated. Instead, client classes that interact with WebLogic Server MBeans should use standard JMX design patterns in which clients use the javax.management.MBeanServerConnection interface to discover MBeans, attributes, and attribute types at runtime. For more information, see 'Developing Manageable Applications with JMX' on http://edocs.bea.com.

webAppContainerType.name: webAppContainerType
webAppContainerType.description: Returns the type of the MBean.

webAppContainerMaxPostSize.name: webAppContainerMaxPostSize
webAppContainerMaxPostSize.description: The maximum post size this server allows for reading HTTP POST data in a servlet request. A value less than 0 indicates an unlimited size.

webAppContainerXPoweredByHeaderLevel.name: webAppContainerXPoweredByHeaderLevel
webAppContainerXPoweredByHeaderLevel.description: WebLogic Server uses the X-Powered-By HTTP header, as recommended by the Servlet 2.4 specification, to publish its implementation information. Following are the options: 'NONE': X-Powered-By header will not be sent 'SHORT' (default): 'Servlet/2.4 JSP/2.0' 'MEDIUM': 'Servlet/2.4 JSP/2.0 (WebLogic/9.1)' 'FULL': 'Servlet/2.4 JSP/1.2 (WebLogic/9.1 JDK/1.4.1_05)'

webAppContainerServletAuthenticationForm.name: webAppContainerServletAuthenticationFormURL
webAppContainerServletAuthenticationForm.description: ServletAuthenticationFormURL is used for backward compatibility with previous releases of Weblogic Server.If ServletAuthenticationFormURL is set to true (default), then ServletAuthentication.getTargetURLForFormAuthentication() and HttpSession.getAttribute(AuthFilter.TARGET_URL) will return the URL of the protected target resource. If set to false, the above API's will return the URI of the protected target resource. By default the value is set to true.(new method added in 9.0.0.1)

webAppContainerReloginEnabled.name: webAppContainerReloginEnabled
webAppContainerReloginEnabled.description: Beginning with the 9.0 release the FORM/BASIC authentication behavior has been modified to conform strictly to the J2EE Specification. If a user has logged-in but does not have privileges to access a resource, the 403 (FORBIDDEN) page will be returned. Turn this flag on to enable the old behavior, which was to return the user to the login form.

webAppContainerWorkContextPropagationEna.name: webAppContainerWorkContextPropagationEnabled
webAppContainerWorkContextPropagationEna.description: Indicates whether or not WorkContextPropagation is enabled. By default it is turned on. There is a little overhead involved in propagating WorkContexts. Therefore, if you don't care about WorkContext propagation, turn this value off in production environments.

webAppContainerRtexprvalueJspParamName.name: webAppContainerRtexprvalueJspParamName
webAppContainerRtexprvalueJspParamName.description: Global property which determines the behavior of the JSP compiler when a jsp:param attribute 'name' has a request time value. Without this property set to 'true', the JSP compiler throws an error for a JSP using a request time value for the 'name' attribute as mandated by the JSP 2.0 spec. This property exists for backward compatibility.

webAppContainerFilterDispatchedRequestsE.name: webAppContainerFilterDispatchedRequestsEnabled
webAppContainerFilterDispatchedRequestsE.description: Indicates whether or not to apply filters to dispatched requests. This is a backward compatibility flag. Until version 8.1, WebLogic Server applied ServletFilters (if configured for the Web application) on request dispatches (and includes/forwards). Servlet 2.4 has introduced the 'Dispatcher' element to make this behavior explicit. The default value is Dispatcher=REQUEST. In order to be complaint with the J2EE specification, the default value for FilterDispatchedRequestsEnabled is false beginning with WebLogic Server 9.0. Note that if you are using old descriptors (meaning web.xml does not have version=2.4), then WebLogic Server automatically uses FilterDispatchedRequestsEnabled = true for the Web applications, unless filter-dispatched-requests-enabled is explicitly set to false in weblogic.xml. This means that old applications will work fine without any modification. Additionally, during migration of old domains to the 9.0 domain, the migration plugin automatically sets this flag to true.

webAppContainerClientCertProxyEnabled.name: webAppContainerClientCertProxyEnabled
webAppContainerClientCertProxyEnabled.description: Specifies whether or not to honor the WL-Proxy-Client-Cert header coming with the request.

webAppContainerOverloadProtectionEnabled.name: webAppContainerOverloadProtectionEnabled
webAppContainerOverloadProtectionEnabled.description: This parameter is used to enable overload protection in the webapp container against low memory conditions. When a low memory situation occurs, new session creation attempts will result in weblogic.servlet.SessionCreationException. The application code needs to catch this exception and take proper action. Alternatively appropriate error-pages can be configured in web.xml against weblogic.servlet.SessionCreationException. This check is performed only on memory and replicated sessions.

webAppContainerOptimisticSerialization.name: webAppContainerOptimisticSerialization
webAppContainerOptimisticSerialization.description: When OptimisticSerialization is turned on, WebLogic server does not serialize-deserialize context and request attributes upon getAttribute(name) when a request gets dispatched across servlet contexts. This means you will need to make sure that the attributes common to Web applications are scoped to a common parent classloader (they are application-scoped) or placed in the system classpath if the two Web applications do not belong to the same application. When OptimisticSerialization is turned off (which is the default) WebLogic Server does serialize-deserialize context and request attributes upon getAttribute(name) to avoid the possibility of ClassCastExceptions. The value of OptimisticSerialization can also be overridden for specific Web applications by setting the optimistic-serialization value in weblogic.xml.

webAppContainerRetainOriginalURL.name: webAppContainerRetainOriginalURL
webAppContainerRetainOriginalURL.description: retain-original-url is used in FORM based authentication scenarios. When this property is set to true, after a successful authentication, Weblogic Server will redirect back to the web resource (page/servlet) retaining the protocol (http/https) used to access the protected resource in the original request. If set to false (which is the default value), Weblogic Server will redirect back to the protected resource using the current protocol. retain-original-url value can also be specified at per webapp level in weblogic.xml. The value in weblogic.xml, if specified, overrides the domain level value.

webAppContainerWeblogicPluginEnabled.name: webAppContainerWeblogicPluginEnabled
webAppContainerWeblogicPluginEnabled.description: Specifies whether or not the proprietary WL-Proxy-Client-IP header should be honored. (This is needed only when WebLogic plugins are configured.)

webAppContainerWAPEnabled.name: webAppContainerWAPEnabled
webAppContainerWAPEnabled.description: Indicates whether the session ID should include JVM information. (Checking this box may be necessary when using URL rewriting with WAP devices that limit the size of the URL to 128 characters, and may also affect the use of replicated sessions in a cluster.) When this box is selected, the default size of the URL will be set at 52 characters, and it will not contain any special characters.

webAppContainerJSPCompilerBackwardsCompa.name: webAppContainerJSPCompilerBackwardsCompatible
webAppContainerJSPCompilerBackwardsCompa.description: Global property to determine the behavior of the JSP compiler. When this property set to 'true', the JSP compiler throws a translation error for JSPs that do not conform to the JSP2.0 specification. This property exists for backward compatibility.

webAppContainerAuthCookieEnabled.name: webAppContainerAuthCookieEnabled
webAppContainerAuthCookieEnabled.description: Whether authcookie feature is enabled or not.

webAppContainerName.name: webAppContainerName
webAppContainerName.description: The user-specified name of this MBean instance. This name is included as one of the key properties in the MBean's javax.management.ObjectName: Name=user-specified-name

webAppContainerAllowAllRoles.name: webAppContainerAllowAllRoles
webAppContainerAllowAllRoles.description: In the security-constraints elements defined in a Web application's web.xml deployment descriptor, the auth-constraint element indicates the user roles that should be permitted access to this resource collection. Here role-name = '*' is a compact syntax for indicating all roles in the Web application. In previous releases, role-name = '*' was treated as all users/roles defined in the realm. This parameter is a backward-compatibility switch to restore old behavior. Default behavior is one required by the spec, meaning all roles defined in the web application. If set, the value defined in weblogic.xml (container-descriptor -> allow-all-roles) takes precedence (if set) over this value.

webAppContainerP3PHeaderValue.name: webAppContainerP3PHeaderValue
webAppContainerP3PHeaderValue.description: Returns the P3PHeader value that will be sent with all responses for http requests (if non-null). The value of this header should set to the location of the policy reference file for the Web site. For details see: http://www.w3.org/TR/p3pdeployment#Locating_PRF Alternatively, a servlet filter can be used to set the P3P header.

webAppContainerMaxPostTimeSecs.name: webAppContainerMaxPostTimeSecs
webAppContainerMaxPostTimeSecs.description: Max Post Time (in seconds) for reading HTTP POST data in a servlet request. MaxPostTime < 0 means unlimited

webAppContainerMimeMappingFile.name: webAppContainerMimeMappingFile
webAppContainerMimeMappingFile.description: Returns the name of the file containing mime-mappings for the domain. Format of the file should be: extension=mime-type Example: htm=text/html gif=image/gif jpg=image/jpeg If this file does not exist, WebLogic Server uses an implicit mime-mapping set of mappings defined in weblogic.utils.http.HttpConstants (DEFAULT_MIME_MAPPINGS). To remove a mapping defined in implicit map just set it to blank.

webAppContainerShowArchivedRealPathEnabl.name: webAppContainerShowArchivedRealPathEnabled
webAppContainerShowArchivedRealPathEnabl.description: Global property to determine the behavior of getRealPath() for archived web applications. When this property set to 'true', getRealPath() will return the canonical path of the resource files.

webAppContainerPostTimeoutSecs.name: webAppContainerPostTimeoutSecs
webAppContainerPostTimeoutSecs.description: The amount of time this server waits between receiving chunks of data in an HTTP POST data before it times out. (This is used to prevent denial-of-service attacks that attempt to overload the server with POST data.)

webServerLogTable.name: webServerLogTable
webServerLogTable.description: Aggregates the logging attributes for the WebServerMBean. Deprecation of MBeanHome and Type-Safe Interfaces This is a type-safe interface for a WebLogic Server MBean, which you can import into your client classes and access through weblogic.management.MBeanHome. As of 9.0, the MBeanHome interface and all type-safe interfaces for WebLogic Server MBeans are deprecated. Instead, client classes that interact with WebLogic Server MBeans should use standard JMX design patterns in which clients use the javax.management.MBeanServerConnection interface to discover MBeans, attributes, and attribute types at runtime. For more information, see 'Developing Manageable Applications with JMX' on http://edocs.bea.com.

webServerLogType.name: webServerLogType
webServerLogType.description: Returns the type of the MBean.

webServerLogLogTimeInGMT.name: webServerLogLogTimeInGMT
webServerLogLogTimeInGMT.description: Specifies whether the time stamps for HTTP log messages are in Greenwich Mean Time (GMT) regardless of the local time zone that the host computer specifies. Use this method to comply with the W3C specification for Extended Format log files. The specification states that all time stamps for Extended Format log entries be in GMT. This method applies only if you have specified the extended message format.

webServerLogNumberOfFilesLimited.name: webServerLogNumberOfFilesLimited
webServerLogNumberOfFilesLimited.description: Indicates whether to limit the number of log files that this server instance creates to store old messages. (Requires that you specify a file rotation type of SIZE or TIME.) After the server reaches this limit, it deletes the oldest log file and creates a new log file with the latest suffix. If you do not enable this option, the server creates new files indefinitely and you must clean up these files as you require.

webServerLogFileTimeSpan.name: webServerLogFileTimeSpan
webServerLogFileTimeSpan.description: The interval (in hours) at which the server saves old log messages to another file. (Requires that you specify a file rotation type of TIME.)

webServerLogLogFileFormat.name: webServerLogLogFileFormat
webServerLogLogFileFormat.description: The format of the HTTP log file. Both formats are defined by the W3C. With the extended log format, you use server directives in the log file to customize the information that the server records.

webServerLogRotationType.name: webServerLogRotationType
webServerLogRotationType.description: Criteria for moving old log messages to a separate file. NONE Messages accumulate in a single file. You must erase the contents of the file when the size is too large. Note that WebLogic Server sets a threshold size limit of 500 MB before it forces a hard rotation to prevent excessive log file growth. SIZE When the log file reaches the size that you specify in FileMinSize, the server renames the file as FileName.n. TIME At each time interval that you specify in TimeSpan, the server renames the file as FileName.n. After the server renames a file, subsequent messages accumulate in a new file with the name that you specified in FileName.

webServerLogFileCount.name: webServerLogFileCount
webServerLogFileCount.description: The maximum number of log files that the server creates when it rotates the log. This number does not include the file that the server uses to store current messages. (Requires that you enable Number of Files Limited.)

webServerLogLoggingEnabled.name: webServerLogLoggingEnabled
webServerLogLoggingEnabled.description: Indicates whether this server logs HTTP requests. (The remaining fields on this page are relevant only if you select this check box.) Gets the loggingEnabled attribute of the WebServerMBean object.

webServerLogELFFields.name: webServerLogELFFields
webServerLogELFFields.description: Returns the list of fields specified for the extended logging format for access.log.

webServerLogFileName.name: webServerLogFileName
webServerLogFileName.description: The name of the log file.

webServerLogFileMinSize.name: webServerLogFileMinSize
webServerLogFileMinSize.description: The size (1 - 65535 kilobytes) that triggers the server to move log messages to a separate file. After the log file reaches the specified minimum size, the next time the server checks the file size, it will rename the current log file as FileName.n and create a new one to store subsequent messages. (Requires that you specify a file rotation type of Size.)

webServerLogBufferSizeKB.name: webServerLogBufferSizeKB
webServerLogBufferSizeKB.description: Gets the underlying log buffer size in kilo bytes

webServerLogDateFormatPattern.name: webServerLogDateFormatPattern
webServerLogDateFormatPattern.description: The date format pattern used for rendering dates in the log. The DateFormatPattern string conforms to the specification of the java.text.SimpleDateFormat class.

webServerLogRotationTime.name: webServerLogRotationTime
webServerLogRotationTime.description: Determines the start time (hour and minute) for a time-based rotation sequence. At the time that this value specifies, the server renames the current log file. Thereafter, the server renames the log file at an interval that you specify in File Time Span. If the specified time has already past, then the server starts its file rotation immediately. Use the following format: k:mm, where k is the hour in a 24-hour format. mm is the minute

webServerLogRotateLogOnStartup.name: webServerLogRotateLogOnStartup
webServerLogRotateLogOnStartup.description: Specifies whether a server rotates its log file during its startup cycle.

webServerLogName.name: webServerLogName
webServerLogName.description: The user-specified name of this MBean instance. This name is included as one of the key properties in the MBean's javax.management.ObjectName: Name=user-specified-name

webServerLogLogFileRotationDir.name: webServerLogLogFileRotationDir
webServerLogLogFileRotationDir.description: The directory where the rotated log files will be stored. By default the rotated files are stored in the same directory where the log file is stored.

webServiceTable.name: webServiceTable
webServiceTable.description: Encapsulates information about a Web Service configuration. Deprecation of MBeanHome and Type-Safe Interfaces This is a type-safe interface for a WebLogic Server MBean, which you can import into your client classes and access through weblogic.management.MBeanHome. As of 9.0, the MBeanHome interface and all type-safe interfaces for WebLogic Server MBeans are deprecated. Instead, client classes that interact with WebLogic Server MBeans should use standard JMX design patterns in which clients use the javax.management.MBeanServerConnection interface to discover MBeans, attributes, and attribute types at runtime. For more information, see 'Developing Manageable Applications with JMX' on http://edocs.bea.com.

webServiceType.name: webServiceType
webServiceType.description: Returns the type of the MBean.

webServiceName.name: webServiceName
webServiceName.description: The user-specified name of this MBean instance. This name is included as one of the key properties in the MBean's javax.management.ObjectName: Name=user-specified-name

webserviceCredentialProviderTable.name: webserviceCredentialProviderTable
webserviceCredentialProviderTable.description: Encapsulates information about a particular credential provider that has been configured for a Web Service security configuration. Deprecation of MBeanHome and Type-Safe Interfaces This is a type-safe interface for a WebLogic Server MBean, which you can import into your client classes and access through weblogic.management.MBeanHome. As of 9.0, the MBeanHome interface and all type-safe interfaces for WebLogic Server MBeans are deprecated. Instead, client classes that interact with WebLogic Server MBeans should use standard JMX design patterns in which clients use the javax.management.MBeanServerConnection interface to discover MBeans, attributes, and attribute types at runtime. For more information, see 'Developing Manageable Applications with JMX' on http://edocs.bea.com.

webserviceCredentialProviderType.name: webserviceCredentialProviderType
webserviceCredentialProviderType.description: Returns the type of the MBean.

webserviceCredentialProviderTokenType.name: webserviceCredentialProviderTokenType
webserviceCredentialProviderTokenType.description: Specifies the type of token used for the particular credential provider or token handler. WebLogic Server supports, by default, three types of tokens: X.509, UsernameToken, and SAML, as specified by the following WS-Security specifications: Web Services Security: Username Token Profile Web Services Security: X.509 Token Profile Web Services Security: SAML Token Profile To specify one of these out-of-the-box types, use these values respectively: 'ut', 'x509', or 'saml'.

webserviceCredentialProviderName.name: webserviceCredentialProviderName
webserviceCredentialProviderName.description: The user-specified name of this MBean instance. This name is included as one of the key properties in the MBean's javax.management.ObjectName: Name=user-specified-name

webserviceCredentialProviderClassName.name: webserviceCredentialProviderClassName
webserviceCredentialProviderClassName.description: The fully qualified name of the class that implements a particular credential provider or token handler.

webserviceSecurityTable.name: webserviceSecurityTable
webserviceSecurityTable.description: Encapsulates information about a Web Service security configuration. Deprecation of MBeanHome and Type-Safe Interfaces This is a type-safe interface for a WebLogic Server MBean, which you can import into your client classes and access through weblogic.management.MBeanHome. As of 9.0, the MBeanHome interface and all type-safe interfaces for WebLogic Server MBeans are deprecated. Instead, client classes that interact with WebLogic Server MBeans should use standard JMX design patterns in which clients use the javax.management.MBeanServerConnection interface to discover MBeans, attributes, and attribute types at runtime. For more information, see 'Developing Manageable Applications with JMX' on http://edocs.bea.com.

webserviceSecurityType.name: webserviceSecurityType
webserviceSecurityType.description: Returns the type of the MBean.

webserviceSecurityDefaultCredentialProvi.name: webserviceSecurityDefaultCredentialProviderSTSURI
webserviceSecurityDefaultCredentialProvi.description: Gets the default STS endpoint URL for all WS-Trust enabled credential providers of this Web Service security configuration.

webserviceSecurityName.name: webserviceSecurityName
webserviceSecurityName.description: The user-specified name of this MBean instance. This name is included as one of the key properties in the MBean's javax.management.ObjectName: Name=user-specified-name

webserviceSecurityPolicySelectionPrefere.name: webserviceSecurityPolicySelectionPreference
webserviceSecurityPolicySelectionPrefere.description: Gets the value of the policySelectionPreference attribute. The preference value can be one of the following: SCP SPC CSP CPS PCS PSC Where: S Security or functionality; C Compatibility or Interoperability; P Performance

webserviceSecurityCompatibilityPreferenc.name: webserviceSecurityCompatibilityPreference
webserviceSecurityCompatibilityPreferenc.description: Gets the value of the compatiblityPreference attribute.

webserviceSecurityTokenType.name: webserviceSecurityTokenType
webserviceSecurityTokenType.description: Returns the type of the MBean.

webserviceSecurityTokenTokenType.name: webserviceSecurityTokenTokenType
webserviceSecurityTokenTokenType.description: Specifies the type of token used for the particular credential provider or token handler. WebLogic Server supports, by default, three types of tokens: X.509, UsernameToken, and SAML, as specified by the following WS-Security specifications: Web Services Security: Username Token Profile Web Services Security: X.509 Token Profile Web Services Security: SAML Token Profile To specify one of these out-of-the-box types, use these values respectively: 'ut', 'x509', or 'saml'.

webserviceSecurityTokenName.name: webserviceSecurityTokenName
webserviceSecurityTokenName.description: The user-specified name of this MBean instance. This name is included as one of the key properties in the MBean's javax.management.ObjectName: Name=user-specified-name

webserviceSecurityTokenClassName.name: webserviceSecurityTokenClassName
webserviceSecurityTokenClassName.description: The fully qualified name of the class that implements a particular credential provider or token handler.

webserviceTimestampType.name: webserviceTimestampType
webserviceTimestampType.description: Returns the type of the MBean.

webserviceTimestampMaxProcessingDelay.name: webserviceTimestampMaxProcessingDelay
webserviceTimestampMaxProcessingDelay.description: Specifies the freshness policy for received messages: the Web Serivce observes the processing delay by subtracting the Created time in the Timestamp from the current time. If the observed processing delay is greater than maxProcessingDelay plus clockSkew, then the message is rejected as stale. This attribute is specified in milliseconds. Setting maxProcessingDelay to NO_MAX_PROCESSING_DELAY disables to enforcement of the freshenss policy.

webserviceTimestampClockSkew.name: webserviceTimestampClockSkew
webserviceTimestampClockSkew.description: ClockSkew takes precedence over ClockPrecision if both are defined, as ClockPrecision has been DEPRECATED. If clocks are synchronized, this attribute describes the accuracy of the synchronization between two clocks: the client and the server. ClockSkew is expressed in milliseconds. Clock skew is enforced by rendering all times into milliseconds since a common time 0 and using these times for comparisons. For example, if you're clocks are accurate to within 1 minute of each other, you would set your skew to 1 minute * 60 seconds * 1000 milliseconds or 60000.

webserviceTimestampClockSynchronized.name: webserviceTimestampClockSynchronized
webserviceTimestampClockSynchronized.description: Specifies whether the Web Service assumes synchronized clocks. If the clockSynchronized attribute is false, the Web Service rejects all inbound messages with that contain expirations, because this is the only safe way to ensure that the message hasn't already expired. In this case, the Web Service also does not enforce a freshness policy. If this attribute is set to true, then the Web Service enforces expirations on inbound messages to the best of its ability and enforces an optional freshness policy (via maxProcessingDelay). The default value of this attribute is true.

webserviceTimestampClockPrecision.name: webserviceTimestampClockPrecision
webserviceTimestampClockPrecision.description: DEPRECATED -- Use set/getClockSkew() -- If both ClockSkew and ClockPrecision are defined, then ClockSkew takes precedence and is used. If clocks are synchronized, this attribute describes the accuracy of the synchronization.

webserviceTimestampValidityPeriod.name: webserviceTimestampValidityPeriod
webserviceTimestampValidityPeriod.description: Represents the length of time the sender wants the outbound message to be valid. When the validityPeriod is positive, the TimestampHandler inserts an Expires element into the Timestamp header. The validityPeriod is expressed in seconds: the Expires time will be that many seconds ahead of the Timestamp's Created time.

webserviceTimestampName.name: webserviceTimestampName
webserviceTimestampName.description: The user-specified name of this MBean instance. This name is included as one of the key properties in the MBean's javax.management.ObjectName: Name=user-specified-name

workManagerTable.name: workManagerTable
workManagerTable.description: Configuration MBean representing WorkManager parameters. A WorkManager configuration can have a RequestClass(FairShare, ResponseTime, ContextBased), MinThreadsConstraint, MaxThreadsConstraint, Capacity and ShutdownTrigger. All these are optional and need to be configured as needed. An empty WorkManager without configuration gets its own default fair share. The default fair share value is 50.

workManagerType.name: workManagerType
workManagerType.description: Returns the type of the MBean.

workManagerDeploymentOrder.name: workManagerDeploymentOrder
workManagerDeploymentOrder.description: A priority that the server uses to determine when it deploys an item. The priority is relative to other deployable items of the same type. For example, the server prioritizes and deploys all EJBs before it prioritizes and deploys startup classes. Items with the lowest Deployment Order value are deployed first. There is no guarantee on the order of deployments with equal Deployment Order values. There is no guarantee of ordering across clusters.

workManagerIgnoreStuckThreads.name: workManagerIgnoreStuckThreads
workManagerIgnoreStuckThreads.description: Specifies whether this Work Manager ignores 'stuck' threads. Normally stuck threads will cause the associated WorkManager to take some action: either switching the application to admin mode, shutting down the server or shutting down the Work Manager. If this flag is set then no thread in this Work Manager is ever considered stuck.

workManagerName.name: workManagerName
workManagerName.description: The user-specified name of this MBean instance. This name is included as one of the key properties in the MBean's javax.management.ObjectName: Name=user-specified-name

workManagerShutdownTriggerTable.name: workManagerShutdownTriggerTable
workManagerShutdownTriggerTable.description: This MBean is used to configure the trigger that shuts down the WorkManager. The trigger specifies the number of threads that need to be stuck for a certain amount of time for the trigger to shutdown the WorkManager automatically. A shutdown WorkManager refuses new work and completes pending work.

workManagerShutdownTriggerType.name: workManagerShutdownTriggerType
workManagerShutdownTriggerType.description: Returns the type of the MBean.

workManagerShutdownTriggerMaxStuckThread.name: workManagerShutdownTriggerMaxStuckThreadTime
workManagerShutdownTriggerMaxStuckThread.description: Time after which a executing thread is declared as stuck.

workManagerShutdownTriggerStuckThreadCou.name: workManagerShutdownTriggerStuckThreadCount
workManagerShutdownTriggerStuckThreadCou.description: Number of stuck threads after which the WorkManager is shutdown

workManagerShutdownTriggerName.name: workManagerShutdownTriggerName
workManagerShutdownTriggerName.description: The user-specified name of this MBean instance. This name is included as one of the key properties in the MBean's javax.management.ObjectName: Name=user-specified-name

deploymentRequestTaskRuntimeTable.name: deploymentRequestTaskRuntimeTable
deploymentRequestTaskRuntimeTable.description: A DeploymentRequestTaskRuntimeMBean provides a container for tasks that collaborate on a DeploymentService request. These are typically a task tracking the application of a configuration change and one or more tasks that involve deployment [application or system resource] actions. This interface provides an overall status of the deployment request progress. Details such as the completion of the task are however dependent on the completion of the subtasks. DeploymentService requests are handled in 2 phases. The first phase - the 'prepare' phase, involves the validation of the request on each target server. Any failure encountered in this validation results in the failure of the overall request. If all targets validate the request properly, the request is considered to be successful and the admin server triggers the 2nd phase - the 'commit . Note that the 'commit' is triggered at the point when the admin server has already determined the request to be successful even though it has not yet completed.

deploymentRequestTaskRuntimeType.name: deploymentRequestTaskRuntimeType
deploymentRequestTaskRuntimeType.description: Returns the type of the MBean.

deploymentRequestTaskRuntimeRunning.name: deploymentRequestTaskRuntimeRunning
deploymentRequestTaskRuntimeRunning.description: Indicates whether the task is still running.

deploymentRequestTaskRuntimeBeginTime.name: deploymentRequestTaskRuntimeBeginTime
deploymentRequestTaskRuntimeBeginTime.description: The time at which this task was started.

deploymentRequestTaskRuntimeEndTime.name: deploymentRequestTaskRuntimeEndTime
deploymentRequestTaskRuntimeEndTime.description: The time at which this task was completed. A value of -1 indicates that the task is currently running.

deploymentRequestTaskRuntimeSystemTask.name: deploymentRequestTaskRuntimeSystemTask
deploymentRequestTaskRuntimeSystemTask.description: Indicates whether this task was initiated by the server versus a user.

deploymentRequestTaskRuntimeName.name: deploymentRequestTaskRuntimeName
deploymentRequestTaskRuntimeName.description: The name of this configuration. WebLogic Server uses an MBean to implement and persist the configuration.

jmsRemoteEndpointRuntimeMessagesCurrentC.name: jmsRemoteEndpointRuntimeMessagesCurrentCount

jmsRemoteEndpointRuntimeBytesCurrentCoun.name: jmsRemoteEndpointRuntimeBytesCurrentCount

jmsRemoteEndpointRuntimeBytesPendingCoun.name: jmsRemoteEndpointRuntimeBytesPendingCount

migrationTaskRuntimeTable.name: migrationTaskRuntimeTable
migrationTaskRuntimeTable.description: Exposes monitoring information about an ongoing and potentially long-running administrative process. This should be taken to mean, at minimum, any OAM operation involving IO. Examples include starting and stopping servers, deploying and undeploying applications, or migrating services. An MBean operation method of this sort should place the actual work on an ExecuteQueue and immediately return an instance of TaskRuntimeMBean to the caller. The caller can then use this to track the task's progress as desired, and if appropriate, provide facilities for user interaction with the task, e.g. 'cancel' or 'continue anyway.' OA&M clients can also query for all instances of TaskRuntimeMBean to get a summary of both currently-running and recently-completed tasks. Instance of TaskRuntimeMBean continue to exist in the MBeanServer after the completion of the work they describe. They will eventually either be explicitly deregistered by an OA&M client, or removed by a scavenger process which periodically purges TaskRuntimeMBeans that have been completed for some time.

serverMigrationRuntimeTable.description: ServerMigrationRuntimeMBean provides runtime monitoring information about the past migrations performed by this server as the cluster master. If this server was never the cluster master then no information would be available. This RuntimeMBean would be hosted on all cluster members and can be queried for the location of the cluster master which is just another peer in the cluster. JMX clients can make another call to the server hosting the cluster master functionality to get the migration history. Please note that the migration history is not persisted and is lost when a server is shutdown.

webServiceOperationRuntimeTable.name: webServiceOperationRuntimeTable
webServiceOperationRuntimeTable.description: Describes the state of an individual webservice operation. This mbean provides some deployment information about the operation (such as it's backend component) as well as detailed performance statistics about its execution. A few notes about these statististics: All times are in milliseconds. Dispatch time refers to the time required to parse an incoming SOAP message and locate an operation to invoke. Excecution time refers to the time required to execute the appropriate method on the backend component, as well as execute all of the service- and operation-level handlers associated with the operation. Response time refers to the time required to construct a SOAP response and send it back to the client. The accuracy of the timings are dependent upon the operating system and JVM in use. In general, timings of very small periods of time are less likely to be accurate, and may be reported as zero.
